{"title_page": "Gorillaz", "text_new": "{{for|the album|Gorillaz (album)}}\n{{short description|British virtual band}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Gorillaz\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Gorillaz band photo.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = From left to right: [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]], [[Murdoc Niccals|Murdoc]], [[2-D (character)|2-D]], [[Russel Hobbs|Russel]]\n| origin           = [[Westbourne Grove]], [[London]], England\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[art pop]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n* {{nowrap|[[trip hop]]}}\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n<!--Please do not add every applicable sub-genre, Template:Infobox musical artist states it should \"aim for generality\".-->\n}}\n| years_active     = 1998\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Parlophone]]\n* [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n* [[Warner Records|Warner]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|<!-- Per Template:Infobox_musical_artist#associated_acts: \"The following uses of this field should be avoided: [...] Groups with only one member in common / One-time collaboration for a single song / Groups that have played or toured together as separate acts / Groups that are merely similar\" -->\n* [[Blur (band)|Blur]]\n* [[The Good, the Bad & the Queen]]\n* [[Monkey: Journey to the West]]\n* [[Spacemonkeyz]]\n* [[Del the Funky Homosapien]]\n* [[De La Soul]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]\n* [[Bobby Womack]]\n* [[Mos Def]]\n* [[Fatoumata Diawara]]\n* [[The Clash]]\n* [[Senseless Things]]\n}}\n| website          = {{url|Gorillaz.com}}\n| current_members  = '''Non-virtual:'''<br>[[Damon Albarn]]<br>[[Jamie Hewlett]]<br>[[Remi Kabaka Jr.]]<br>'''Virtual:'''<br>[[2-D (character)|2-D]]<br>[[Murdoc Niccals]]<br>[[Russel Hobbs]]<br>[[Noodle (character)|Noodle]]\n| past_members     = '''Virtual:'''<br>Paula Cracker<br>Cyborg Noodle<br>[[Ace (The Powerpuff Girls)|Ace]]\n}}\n'''Gorillaz''' are <!--This article is written in British English, which treats collective nouns plural, Do not change \"are\" to \"is\". Too, don't remove \"British virtual band\" to \"English virtual band\".--> a British [[virtual band]] created in 1998 by [[Damon Albarn]] and artist [[Jamie Hewlett]]. The band primarily consists of four animated members: [[2-D (character)|Stuart \"2-D\" Pot]], [[Murdoc Niccals]], [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]], and [[Russel Hobbs]]. Their [[fictional universe]] is presented in music videos, interviews and short cartoons. In reality, Albarn is the only permanent musical contributor, and he often collaborates with other musicians.  [[Remi Kabaka Jr.]] became producer for the band in 2016 after several years providing the voice of [[Russel Hobbs]] and was listed as an official member alongside Albarn and Hewlett in the 2019 Gorillaz documentary ''Gorillaz: Reject False Icons''.<ref>{{cite AV media |last=Hewlett |first=Denholm |date=24 December 2019 |title=Gorillaz: Reject False Icons (Director's Cut) |medium=Motion picture |url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=qGKgMuYKqf4 |access-date=5 January 2020 |time=23:32 |location=YouTube |publisher=Gorillaz}}</ref> \n\nWith Gorillaz, Albarn departed from the distinct [[Britpop]] of his band [[Blur (band)|Blur]] through [[hip hop]], [[electronic music]], and [[world music]] through an \"eccentrically [[postmodern]]\" approach.<ref name=\"mfHZ\" /> The band's 2001 debut album ''[[Gorillaz (album)|Gorillaz]]'' went triple platinum in the UK and double platinum in Europe and earned the group an entry in the ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World Records]]'' as the Most Successful Virtual Band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inthenews.co.uk/entertainment/reviews/music/r-n-b-rap/gorillaz-d-sides-$1170827.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418193200/http://www.inthenews.co.uk/entertainment/reviews/music/r-n-b-rap/gorillaz-d-sides-$1170827.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 April 2010|title=WebCite query result|website=www.webcitation.org|language=en|access-date=6 July 2018}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Mercury Prize]], but the nomination was withdrawn at the band's request.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1454491.stm|title=Mercury Music Prize: The nominees|accessdate=7 September 2007|date=25 July 2001|work=[[BBC News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124123736/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1454491.stm|archivedate=24 November 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Their second studio album, ''[[Demon Days]]'' (2005), went six times platinum in the UK<ref name=\"Platinum UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|title=Certified Awards Search|accessdate=17 January 2010|date=24 February 2006|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] <!-- Search for \"Gorillaz\" -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704041118/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|archivedate=4 July 2011}}</ref> and [[Music recording sales certification|double platinum]] in the US.<ref name=\"Platinum US\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Gorillaz&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50 |title=Gorillaz RIAA certifications |accessdate=7 December 2008 |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903230335/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Gorillaz&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50 |archivedate=3 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=2006grammynomination>{{cite news|url=http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2005/Press35.htm|title=EMI Music earns 54 Grammy nominations|accessdate=1 June 2007|date=8 December 2005|publisher=[[EMI]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508024333/http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2005/Press35.htm|archivedate=8 May 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.emimusicpub.com/news/emi-music-publishing-wins-big-at-the-grammys!.php|title=EMI Music Publishing Wins Big at the Grammys!|accessdate=17 January 2010|date=14 February 2006|publisher=[[EMI]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929161637/http://emimusicpub.com/news/emi-music-publishing-wins-big-at-the-grammys!.php|archivedate=29 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe third Gorillaz studio album, ''[[Plastic Beach]]'', was released on 3 March 2010. The fourth, ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]'', was released on 25 December 2010 as a surprise gift for paying fan club members, then on 18 April 2011 as an official release. The fifth, ''[[Humanz]]'', was released after a six-year hiatus on 28 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/61678-gorillaz-announce-new-album-humanz-featuring-grace-jones-danny-brown-mavis-staples-more/|title=Gorillaz Announce New Album Humanz Featuring Grace Jones, Danny Brown, Mavis Staples, More|website=Pitchfork|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref> Their sixth studio album, ''[[The Now Now]]'', was released on 29 June 2018.\nGorillaz are currently working on a project named ''[[Song Machine]]'' which releases new songs every month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gorillaz.lnk.to/TNN?ref=https://www.youtube.com/|title=The Now Now by Gorillaz|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGorillaz [[List of awards and nominations received by Gorillaz|have won]] one [[Grammy Award]], two [[MTV Video Music Awards]], an [[NME Award]] and three [[MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref>[http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-g/gorillaz.htm Rock On The Net: Gorillaz] Rock on the Net</ref> They have been nominated for ten [[Brit Award]]s and won [[Brit Award for British Group|Best British Group]] at the [[2018 Brit Awards]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42677246 \"Brit Awards 2018: The winners and nominees\"]. BBC. Retrieved 21 February 2018</ref><ref name=\"Brit Awards\">[http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/gorillaz Gorillaz BRITS Profile]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202033222/http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/gorillaz|date=2 February 2012}} BRIT Awards Ltd</ref> By 2010, Gorillaz had sold over 20 million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jim|last=Harrington|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2010/10/30/review-gorillaz-not-monkeying-around-with-virtual-band-anymore/|title=Review: Gorillaz not monkeying around with virtual band anymore/|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|date=30 October 2010|access-date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Creation (1990\u20131999)===\n[[File:Damon Albarn - Gorillaz - Roskilde Festival 2010.jpg|thumb|left|[[Damon Albarn]], co-creator of Gorillaz]]\nMusician [[Damon Albarn]] and comic creator [[Jamie Hewlett]] met in 1990 when guitarist [[Graham Coxon]], a fan of Hewlett's work, asked him to interview [[Blur (band)|Blur]], a band Albarn and Coxon had recently formed.<ref name=\"Elliot\">{{cite journal|last=Elliot|first=Paul|date=August 2001|title=FEATURE: Damon and Jamie Interview. HEY HEY WE\u2019RE THE MONKEYS!|url=http://gorillaz-news.livejournal.com/11140.html|journal=[[Q magazine|Q]]|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> The interview was published in [[Deadline (magazine)|''Deadline'']] magazine, home of Hewlett's [[comic strip]] ''[[Tank Girl]]''. Hewlett initially thought Albarn was \"arsey, a wanker\"; despite becoming acquaintances with the band, they often did not get on, especially after Hewlett began seeing Coxon's ex-girlfriend Jane Olliver.<ref name=Elliot /> Despite this, Albarn and Hewlett started sharing a flat on [[Westbourne Grove]] in London in 1997.<ref>{{cite journal |first = Chris |last = Heath |authorlink = Chris Heath |date=November 2007 |url=http://www.vblurpage.com/articles/stories/q_07.htm |title = The 21 People Who Changed Music: Damon Albarn |journal = [[Q (magazine)|Q]] |page = 87 |accessdate =24 April 2017}}</ref> Hewlett had recently broken up with Olliver and Albarn was at the end of his highly publicised relationship with [[Justine Frischmann]] of [[Elastica]].<ref name=Elliot />\n\nThe idea to create Gorillaz came about when Albarn and Hewlett were watching [[MTV]]. Hewlett said, \"If you watch MTV for too long, it's a bit like hell&nbsp;\u2013 there's nothing of substance there. So we got this idea for a virtual band, something that would be a comment on that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.07/gorillaz.html |title=Keeping It (Un)real|accessdate=5 October 2008|first=Neil|last=Gaiman|authorlink=Neil Gaiman|date=July 2005|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105225835/http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.07/gorillaz.html|archivedate=5 January 2010|url-status=live}}<!-- Page 2 archive URL: https://www.webcitation.org/5mqkDI6O2?url=http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.07/gorillaz.html?pg%3D2%26topic%3Dgorillaz%26topic_set%3D --></ref> The band originally identified themselves as \"Gorilla\" and the first song they recorded was \"Ghost Train\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1503836/060905/gorillaz.jhtml|title=Gorillaz: Who Can It Be Now?|accessdate=10 October 2007|first=Jim|last=Macnie|date=9 June 2005|publisher=[[VH1]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506223813/http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1503836/060905/gorillaz.jhtml|archivedate=6 May 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> which was later released as a [[B-side]] on their single \"[[Rock the House (Gorillaz song)|Rock the House]]\" and the B-side compilation ''[[G Sides]]''. The musicians behind Gorillaz' first incarnation included Albarn, [[Del the Funky Homosapien]], [[Dan the Automator]] and [[Kid Koala]], who had previously worked together on the track \"Time Keeps on Slipping\" for [[Deltron 3030]]'s [[Deltron 3030 (album)|eponymous debut album]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r480919|pure_url=yes}}|title=Deltron 3030 review|accessdate=27 March 2007|first=Steve|last=Huey|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\nAlthough not released under the Gorillaz name, Albarn has said that \"one of the first ever Gorillaz tunes\" was [[Blur (band)|Blur]]'s 1997 single \"[[On Your Own (Blur song)|On Your Own]]\", which was released for their fifth studio album ''[[Blur (Blur album)|Blur]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/media/s2854145.htm|last1=McDougall|first1=Lindsay|title=Gorillaz's Damon Albarn interview (part 2)|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Gorillaz'' (2000\u201303) ===\n{{listen\n|filename=Gorillaz - Clint Eastwood (sample).ogg\n|title=\"Clint Eastwood\"\n|description=\"[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\" exemplifies the mix of musical styles found on the band's debut album, combining hip hop, electronic and dub influences. The verses are rapped by [[Del the Funky Homosapien]] and the chorus is sung by [[Damon Albarn]].\n}}\nThe band's first release was the [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Tomorrow Comes Today]]'', released on 27 November 2000. The band's first single was \"[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\" and was released on 5 March 2001. It was produced by [[hip hop music|hip hop]] producer [[Dan the Automator]] and originally featured UK rap group [[Phi Life Cypher]], but the version that appears on the album features American rapper [[Del the Funky Homosapien]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/sep01/articles/gorillaztracks.asp|title=Recording Gorillaz's 'Clint Eastwood'|work=Sound on Sound|accessdate=20 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225224656/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/sep01/articles/gorillaztracks.asp|archivedate=25 December 2011}}</ref> known on the album as ''Del tha' Ghost Rapper'', a spirit in the band's drummer [[Russel Hobbs]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Cass|authorlink=Cass Browne|author2=Gorillaz|title=[[Rise of the Ogre]]|date=2 November 2006|publisher=Penguin|location=United States|isbn=1-59448-931-9|page=41}}</ref> The Phi Life Cypher version of \"Clint Eastwood\" appears on the B-side album ''[[G Sides]]''. On 26 March 2001, their first full-length album, the [[eponym|self-titled]] ''[[Gorillaz (album)|Gorillaz]]'', was released, producing four singles: \"[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\", \"[[19-2000]]\", \"[[Rock the House (Gorillaz song)|Rock the House]]\", and \"[[Tomorrow Comes Today]]\". In June 2001, \"19\u20132000\" a remix of the song was used as the title theme for [[EA Sports]] ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA]]'' video game ''[[FIFA Football 2002]]''.<ref name=\"Singles chart\">David Roberts (2006). [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]. London: Guinness World Records Limited</ref>\n\nOn 7 December, the song \"[[911 (Gorillaz song)|911]]\" was released, a collaboration between Gorillaz and hip hop group [[D12 (band)|D12]] (without [[Eminem]]) and [[Terry Hall (singer)|Terry Hall]] about the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Cass|authorlink=Cass Browne|author2=Gorillaz|title=[[Rise of the Ogre]]|date=2 November 2006|publisher=Penguin|location=United States|isbn=1-59448-931-9|page=99}}</ref> Meanwhile, ''G Sides'', a compilation of the B-sides from the ''Tomorrow Comes Today'' EP and first three singles, was released in Japan on 12 December. Gorillaz performed at the [[2002 Brit Awards]] in London on 22 February, appearing in [[3D animation]] on four large screens along with rap accompaniment by [[Phi Life Cypher]]. The band were nominated for four [[Brit Awards]], including [[Brit Award for British Group|Best British Group]], Best British Album and [[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1760402.stm|title=Brit Awards 2002: The nominations|accessdate=11 February 2009|date=14 January 2002|work=BBC News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111005221/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1760402.stm|archivedate=11 November 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> but did not win any awards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/G/Gorillaz/2002/02/23/745445.html|title=Gorillaz come out of the mist|accessdate=11 February 2009|first=Kieran|last=Grant|date=23 February 2002|work=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120709161655/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/G/Gorillaz/2002/02/23/745445.html|archivedate=9 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2002, a [[remix album]] titled ''[[Laika Come Home]]'' by [[Spacemonkeyz]] vs. Gorillaz was released. It contains most of the songs from  Gorillaz' first album, ''Gorillaz'', but remixed in [[Dub music|dub]] and [[reggae]] style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/gorillaz/6476|title=NME Album Reviews \u2013 Space Monkeys vs. Gorillaz: Laika Come Home|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> On 18 November, a DVD titled ''[[Phase One: Celebrity Take Down]]'' was released. The DVD contains four promotional videos, the abandoned video for \"[[5/4 (song)|5/4]]\", the ''Charts of Darkness'' documentary, the five Gorilla Bitez (comedic shorts starring the virtual characters), a tour of the website by the MEL 9000 server and more. The DVD's menu was designed much like the band's website and depicts an abandoned Kong Studios.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/18165-phase-one-celebrity-take-down-dvd|title=Phase One: Celebrity Take Down DVD|accessdate=11 February 2009|first=Rob|last=Mitchum|date=5 February 2003|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104010306/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/3525-phase-one-celebrity-take-down-dvd/|archivedate=4 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nRumours were circulating at this time that the Gorillaz team were busy preparing a film, but Hewlett said that the film project had been abandoned: \"We lost all interest in doing it as soon as we started meeting with studios and talking to these Hollywood executive types, we just weren't on the same page. We said, fuck it, we'll sit on the idea until we can do it ourselves, and maybe even raise the money ourselves.\"<ref name=\"Big Issue\">{{cite journal|last=Joseph|first=Michael|date=2 November 2006|title=Gorillaz in the Midst|journal=[[The Big Issue]] in Scotland|issue=604|page=13}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Demon Days'' (2004\u201306) ===\nThe album ''[[Demon Days]]'' was released on 11 May 2005. The album debuted at No.&nbsp;1 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/album/13902|title=Gorillaz&nbsp;\u2013 Demon Days&nbsp;\u2013 Music Charts|accessdate=9 October 2007|work=\u03b1Charts.us}}</ref> The third single was \"[[Dirty Harry (song)|Dirty Harry]]\", which had been released as a promotional single earlier that year. It was released in the United Kingdom on 21 November. The fourth and final single was a [[double A-side]], \"[[Kids with Guns]]\" / \"[[El Ma\u00f1ana (song)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]\". It was released in the UK on 10 April 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/discog/elmanana.php |title=El Ma\u00f1ana / Kids With Guns |accessdate=7 March 2007 |year=2006 |work=fans.gorillaz.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107173510/http://fans.gorillaz.com/discog/elmanana.php |archivedate=7 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In December 2005, ''Demon Days'' had sold over a million copies in the UK, making it the UK's fifth best selling album of 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.bpi.co.uk/news/printerFriendly/print.asp?nwz_id=news_content_file_966.shtml |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160411081626/http://www.bpi.co.uk/news/printerFriendly/print.asp?nwz_id=news_content_file_966.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-date = 11 April 2016 |title = UK record industry releases 2005 sales figures |accessdate =7 December 2008 |date = 6 January 2006 |publisher = [[British Phonographic Industry]] }}</ref> ''Demon Days'' has since gone six times platinum in the UK,<ref name=\"Platinum UK\"/> double platinum in the United States,<ref name=\"Platinum US\"/> triple platinum in Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/ARIACharts-Accreditations-2006Albums.htm |title=ARIA Charts&nbsp;\u2013 Accreditations&nbsp;\u2013 2006 Albums |accessdate=3 April 2007 |year=2006 |publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102034739/http://www.aria.com.au/pages/ARIACharts-Accreditations-2006Albums.htm |archivedate=2 January 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and has sold over 8&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emimusicpub.com/worldwide/artist_profile/gorillaz_profile.html |title=Artist Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gorillaz |accessdate=7 December 2008 |year=2006 |publisher=[[EMI]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081115114738/http://www.emimusicpub.com/worldwide/artist_profile/gorillaz_profile.html |archivedate=15 November 2008 }}</ref> At the [[2005 MTV Video Music Awards]] in Miami on 28 August, Gorillaz won two awards for \"[[Feel Good Inc.]]\" featuring [[De La Soul]], including the award for [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video|Breakthrough Video]].<ref>[http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2005/mtvvmas.htm 2005 MTV Video Music Awards] Rock on the Net. Retrieved 7 December 2011</ref>\n\n[[File:De La Soul Demon Days Live.jpg|thumb|left|[[De La Soul]] performing \"Feel Good Inc.\" with Gorillaz at the [[Demon Days Live]] concert in Manchester, England]]\nGorillaz performed \"Dirty Harry\" at the [[2006 Brit Awards]] in London, and the band were nominated for [[Brit Award for British Group|Best British Group]], and Best British Album (''Demon Days'').<ref name=\"Brit Awards\"/> Plans were unveiled for Gorillaz to go on a \"holographic\" world tour in 2007 and 2008.<ref name=\"worldtour\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/sep/08/gorillaz.popandrock |title=Gorillaz to tour&nbsp;\u2013 in 3D |accessdate=11 October 2008 |first=Dave |last=Simpson |date=8 September 2008 |work=The Guardian |location=UK |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015122232/http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2005/sep/08/gorillaz.popandrock |archivedate=15 October 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The virtual members would be shown as virtual characters on stage using [[Musion Eyeliner]] technology, giving them a lifelike appearance on stage. The virtual characters were first used at the [[2005 MTV Europe Music Awards]] on 3 November,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_case_study.html |title=Gorillaz at the MTV Awards 2005 |accessdate=9 September 2007 |year=2006 |publisher=Dimensional Studios |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329154828/http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_case_study.html |archivedate=29 March 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and again at the [[48th Grammy Awards|2006 Grammy Awards]], on 8 February 2006 with the addition of [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], where the band played a pre-recorded version of \"Feel Good Inc.\"<ref name=\"Grammy Madonna\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_madonna_grammy_awards.html |title=Gorillaz & Madonna&nbsp;\u2013 Grammy Awards 2006 |accessdate=5 November 2006 |year=2006 |publisher=Dimensional Studios |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304115414/http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_madonna_grammy_awards.html |archivedate=4 March 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:GorillazKidrobot.jpg|thumb|right|All the Kidrobot figures that were released. The black set, red set, special \"[[Dare (song)|Dare]]\" [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]], four-color set, white set and two-tone set]]\nDuring 16 October\u20132 November, a set of Gorillaz figures were released by [[Kidrobot]] to coincide with the release of ''[[Demon Days]]''. Two variations of the set were released, known as the Red and Black editions, and a limited edition [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]] from the music video for \"[[Dare (song)|Dare]]\" was also released.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/62712/gorillaz-going-out-on-virtual-us-tour \"Gorillaz going out on virtual U.S. tour\"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 30 July 2015</ref> Three new sets of Gorillaz vinyl figures were released in 2006. The basic set which was limited to 60,000 was the two-tone set limited to 1,000 and the white edition which was limited to 4,000 were released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.virginrecords.com/home/news.aspx?&action=search&Keyword=Gorillaz%20Phase%20Two&submitButton=Search |title=Gorillaz Phase Two&nbsp;\u2013 Slowboat to Hades DVD Released 31&nbsp;October |accessdate=7 December 2008 |date=9 October 2006 |publisher=[[Virgin Records]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130205152618/http://www.virginrecords.com/home/news.aspx?&action=search&Keyword=Gorillaz+Phase+Two&submitButton=Search|archivedate=5 February 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> On 26 October, the Gorillaz [[autobiography]] titled ''[[Rise of the Ogre]]'' by [[Riverhead Books]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9781594489310,00.html|title=Rise of the Ogre (US)|accessdate=2007-08-27|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200126/http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0%2C%2C9781594489310%2C00.html|archivedate=2007-09-30|df=}}</ref> was released on UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penguin.co.uk/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780718150006,00.html|title=Rise of the Ogre (UK)|accessdate=2007-08-27|date=26 October 2006|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915173058/http://www.penguin.co.uk/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780718150006,00.html|archivedate=2007-09-15|df=}}</ref> 2 November 2006 on US. On 30 October, the ''[[Phase Two: Slowboat to Hades]]'' DVD was released on UK. 25 October in Japan. 31 October in the US. And 11 November in Australia. It contains the most of the materials released by Gorillaz from 2004 to 2006. The MTV EMAs, Grammys and Brits live performances. Also included is the Gorillaz' ''[[MTV Cribs]]'' episode, the Phase Two Gorillaz bites, a new Kong Studios guide, a gallery, and short interviews.\n\nOn 2 June 2006 the hopes for a Gorillaz film were revived, when Hewlett stated that they would be producing the film on their own. Film producer and [[The Weinstein Company]] co-chairman, [[Harvey Weinstein]], was said to be in talks with Albarn and Hewlett.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20060602013348612 |title=Gorillaz: The Movie |accessdate=1 October 2006 |first=Peter |last=Sciretta |date=2 June 2006 |work=[[/Film]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404133619/http://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20060602013348612 |archivedate=4 April 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In a September 2006 interview with [[Uncut (magazine)|''Uncut'']] magazine, Albarn was said that the band \"has been a fantastic journey which isn't over, because we're making a film. We've got [[Terry Gilliam]] involved. But as far as being in a big band and putting pop music out there, it's finished. We won't be doing that any more.\"<ref name=\"Uncut\">{{cite journal |last = Williamson |first = Nigel |date=November 2006 |title = West London Calling |journal = [[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |page = 88}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2007, a [[compilation album]] titled ''[[D-Sides]]'' was released. It contains [[A-side and B-side|B-sides]] and [[remix]]es from [[single (music)|singles]] and [[bonus tracks]] for the band's second [[studio album]] ''[[Demon Days]]'', as well as previously unreleased tracks recorded during the same sessions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#070918|title=D-Sides Confirmed|accessdate=19 September 2007|date=18 September 2007|work=fans.gorillaz.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324065333/http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#070918|archivedate=24 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#071020|title=D-Sides Deluxe Preview|accessdate=3 November 2007|date=20 October 2007|work=fans.gorillaz.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324065333/http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#071020|archivedate=24 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Only one video out in 8 December 2004, \"[[Rockit (Gorillaz song)|Rockit]] (or \"Rock It\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Cass|authorlink=Cass Browne|author2=Gorillaz|title=[[Rise of the Ogre]]|date=2 November 2006|publisher=Penguin|location=United States|isbn=1-59448-931-9|page=204}}</ref> On 20 April 2009, a [[documentary]] titled ''[[Bananaz]]'', was released on [[PAL]] / [[Region 0]] DVD format. It contains the [[documentary film]], directed by Ceri Levy, documents the previous seven years of the band.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bananaz: Dir. Ceri Levy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/15/damon-albarn-gorillaz|accessdate=30 September 2018|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=19 April 2009}}</ref> The film was released online on the [[Babelgum]] website on 20 April 2009 followed by the DVD release on 1 June 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorillaz go Bananaz online |url=http://news.qthemusic.com/2009/04/gorillaz_movie_set_for_online.html|work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|date=9 April 2009|accessdate=17 January 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715134518/http://news.qthemusic.com/2009/04/gorillaz_movie_set_for_online.html|archivedate=15 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Plastic Beach'' and ''The Fall'' (2007\u201313) ===\n{{Listen|filename=Gorillaz - Stylo (Sample).ogg|title=\"Stylo\"|description=Featuring [[Mos Def]] and [[Bobby Womack]], \"[[Stylo (song)|Stylo]]\" contained [[Electronic music|electronic]] influences.}}\nIn late 2007, Albarn and Hewlett began working on ''Carousel'', a new Gorillaz project which eventually evolved into the band's third studio album ''[[Plastic Beach]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last = Lynskey |first = Dorian |date=December 2007 |title = Damon Albarn |journal = [[Q (magazine)|Q]]}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian 2009\">{{cite news|last=Morley|first=Paul|url=http://audio.theguardian.tv/audio/kip/music/series/paul-morley-showing-off/1259329339795/8827/AlbarnMorleyFINAL.mp3|title=Paul Morley's Showing Off... Damon Albarn|date=27 November 2009|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=29 November 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5le8WXHB0?url=http://audio.theguardian.tv/audio/kip/music/series/paul-morley-showing-off/1259329339795/8827/AlbarnMorleyFINAL.mp3|archivedate=29 November 2009|format=MP3|authorlink=Paul Morley}}<!-- Article URL: http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/nov/28/showing-off-damon-albarn --></ref>\n\nAlbarn said \"I'm making this the biggest and most pop record I've ever made in many ways, but with all my experience to try and at least present something that has got depth.\"<ref name=\"guardian 2009\" /> The album features guest performances by [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Lou Reed]], [[Mos Def]], [[Bobby Womack]], [[Gruff Rhys]], [[Mark E. Smith]], [[Mick Jones (The Clash)|Mick Jones]], [[Paul Simonon]], [[Kano (rapper)|Kano]], [[Bashy]], [[De La Soul]], [[Little Dragon]], [[Hypnotic Brass Ensemble]], [[sinfonia ViVA]], and the Lebanese National Orchestra for Oriental Arabic Music.<ref name=\"guardian 2009\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/05/de-la-nike.html |title=De La Soul's Posdnuos on their Nike mix, their next album, and working again with Gorillaz |accessdate=29 May 2009 |first=Simon |last=Vozick-Levinson |date=28 May 2009 |work=Entertainment Weekly |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815140629/http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/05/28/de-la-nike/ |archivedate=15 August 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Pitchfork>{{cite news|title=Gorillaz Reveal Full Album Details |first=Amy |last=Phillips |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/37638-gorillaz-reveal-full-album-details/ |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=20 January 2010 |accessdate=21 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123125020/http://pitchfork.com/news/37638-gorillaz-reveal-full-album-details/ |archivedate=23 January 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2010, it was announced that Gorillaz would be headlining the final night of the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] on 18 April 2010.<ref name=\"coachella\">{{cite news|title=2010 Coachella Line Up is here |url=http://coachella.com/updates/news/2010lineup |publisher=[[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] |date=18 January 2010 |accessdate=20 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123000304/http://coachella.com/updates/news/2010lineup |archivedate=23 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\nThe first single from the album, \"[[Stylo (song)|Stylo]]\", featuring Bobby Womack and Mos Def was made available for download 26 January 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Gorillaz Song 'Stylo' Hits The Web |first=James |last=Montgomery |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1630062/20100120/gorillaz.jhtml |work=[[MTV News]] |date=20 January 2010 |accessdate=21 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123020030/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1630062/20100120/gorillaz.jhtml |archivedate=23 January 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In October 2010, Albarn announced to the media that he would not let the cast of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' cover the band's songs, claiming that the music on the Fox network's TV show is a \"very poor substitute for the real thing\". This statement led most people to believe that Gorillaz had been asked by ''Glee'' producers to lend their music to the show, which they had not. Albarn responded to the confusion with a laugh and said \"and now they definitely won't.\"<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/954190/gorillaz-we-wont-let-glee-cover-our-songs |title = Gorillaz: We Won't Let 'Glee' Cover Our Songs |work = Billboard |date = 14 September 2009 |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 October 2010, Gorillaz announced their new single \"[[Doncamatic]]\" featuring [[Daley (musician)|Daley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gorillaz.com/news/news/breaking-news-brand-new-gorillaz-single-to-be-played-on-zane-lowe-show-youtube-tonight |title=News \u2013 BREAKING NEWS! Brand new Gorillaz single to be played on Zane Lowe show & Youtube tonight! |publisher=Gorillaz.com |date=5 October 2010 |accessdate=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711113046/http://gorillaz.com/news/news/breaking-news-brand-new-gorillaz-single-to-be-played-on-zane-lowe-show-youtube-tonight |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> On 8 December 2010, Albarn confirmed that a Gorillaz album recorded on the American leg of the Escape to Plastic Beach tour would be released to download for free exclusively to paying fan club members from the Gorillaz website on Christmas Day, 25 December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/entertainment/8473116/gorillaz-in-the-hits/ |title = Gorillaz in the hits \u2013 The West Australian |work = Yahoo! News |date = 8 December 2010 |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref> The video for \"[[Phoner to Arizona]]\" was released on Gorillaz' website for free on 24 December and, a day later, their new album was released, entitled ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://pitchfork.com/news/41023-gorillaz-name-ipad-album/ |title = Gorillaz Name iPad Album |work = Pitchfork |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2011, Gorillaz announced the release of their own version of the iPad app iElectribe, by [[Korg]] \u2013 which features loops and samples taken from ''The Fall'' as well as other samples. The new version features a Gorillaz designed and styled interface; it is customised to generate Gorillaz samples from their album ''The Fall'' and includes 128 new sounds created by the band and 64 ready-to-use pre-programmed patterns from Gorillaz, Stephen Sedgwick (Gorillaz' engineer) and [[Korg]]. The app was based on Korg's Electribe: R device app.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.gorillaz-unofficial.com/news/index.htm |title = GorillazUnofficial 100% unofficial. 100% Gorillaz |publisher = Gorillaz-unofficial.com |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/korg-ielectribe-gorillaz-edition/id430288460?mt%3D8 |title = KORG iELECTRIBE Gorillaz Edition for iPad on the iTunes App Store |publisher = iTunes Store |date = 26 May 2011 |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref> On 5 October 2011, Gorillaz released their first \"greatest hits\" compilation, ''[[The Singles Collection 2001\u20132011]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gorillaz.com/news/news/10-years-of-gorillaz-the-singles-collection |title=News \u2013 10 Years of Gorillaz! |date=5 October 2011 |accessdate=15 October 2011 |publisher=Gorillaz |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007235018/http://gorillaz.com/news/news/10-years-of-gorillaz-the-singles-collection |archivedate=7 October 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2012, Gorillaz announced \"[[DoYaThing]]\", a single to promote the Gorillaz-branded [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] shoes that were soon to be released. The song would be part of Converse's \"Three Artists, One Song\" projects, with the two collaborators being [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] of [[LCD Soundsystem]] and [[Andr\u00e9 3000]] of [[Outkast]]. An explicit, 13-minute-long version of the song became available for listening shortly after on Gorillaz.com. Hewlett returned to direct the single's music video, featuring animated versions of the two collaborators on the track.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gorillaz-unofficial.com/news/ |title=GorillazUnofficial 100% unofficial. 100% Gorillaz |publisher=Gorillaz-unofficial.com |accessdate=31 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326063451/http://gorillaz-unofficial.com/news/ |archivedate=26 March 2012  }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, Albarn told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he and Hewlett had fallen out and that future Gorillaz projects were \"unlikely\".<ref name=\"harris1\">{{cite news |title=Damon Albarn: Gorillaz, heroin and the last days of Blur |author=Harris, John |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/apr/07/damon-albarn-gorillaz-heroin-blur? |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group plc|Guardian News and Media]] |location=London/Manchester |date=7 April 2012 |page=1 |accessdate=7 April 2012 }}</ref> Tension between the two had been building, partly due to a belief held by Hewlett that his contributions to Gorillaz were being diminished. Speaking to ''The Guardian'' in April 2017, Hewlett explained: \"Damon had half the Clash on stage, and Bobby Womack and Mos Def and De La Soul, and fucking Hypnotic Brass Ensemble and Bashy and everyone else. It was the greatest band ever. And the screen on stage behind them seemed to get smaller every day. I\u2019d say, \u2018Have we got a new screen?\u2019 and the tour manager was like, \u2018No, it\u2019s the same screen.\u2019 Because it seemed to me like it was getting smaller.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Damon Albarn and Jamie Hewlett: \u2018We fight over everything\u2019 |author=Sawyer, Miranda |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/apr/30/damon-albarn-and-jamie-hewlett-we-fight-over-everything-gorillaz-humanz-interview |work=The Guardian |date=30 April 2017 |accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref> On 25 April 2012, in an interview with Metro, Albarn was more optimistic about Gorillaz' future, saying that once he had worked out his differences with Hewlett, he was sure that they would make another record.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams |first=Andrew |url=http://www.metro.co.uk/music/897126-damon-albarn-blur-and-gorillaz-arent-finished-yet |title=Damon Albarn: Blur and Gorillaz aren't finished yet &#124; Metro News |work=Metro|location=UK |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> On 24 June 2013, Hewlett stated that he and Albarn planned to someday record a follow-up to their 2010 album ''[[Plastic Beach]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Guardian music |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jun/24/blur-gorillaz-new-albums-damon-albarn |title=Blur and Gorillaz will both make new albums, says Albarn collaborator  |work=The Guardian |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/51295-blur-and-gorillaz-will-release-new-albums-gorillaz-jamie-hewlett-says/ |title=Blur and Gorillaz Will Release New Albums, Gorillaz' Jamie Hewlett Says  |work=Pitchfork |date=24 June 2013 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Humanz'' (2014\u201317) ===\nIn April 2014, Albarn told the ''[[National Post]]'' that he \"wouldn't mind having another stab at a Gorillaz record.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = http://arts.nationalpost.com/2014/04/29/i-dont-take-britpop-seriously-and-no-one-should-damon-albarn-does-a-rare-bit-of-looking-back-on-his-first-solo-record/ |archive-url = https://archive.today/20140501210752/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2014/04/29/i-dont-take-britpop-seriously-and-no-one-should-damon-albarn-does-a-rare-bit-of-looking-back-on-his-first-solo-record/ |url-status=dead |archive-date = 1 May 2014 |title = 'I don't take Britpop seriously and no one should': Damon Albarn does a rare bit of looking back on his first solo record, Everyday Robots |first = Jonathan |last = Dekel |date = 29 April 2014 |work = National Post }}</ref> Two months later he reported that he had \"been writing quite a lot of songs on the road for Gorillaz\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2014/06/bonnaroo-2014-damon-albarn-interview|title=Damon Albarn Hypes Up New Gorillaz Tracks|publisher=Fuse|date=15 June 2014|accessdate=19 October 2014|author=Xu, Tina|page=1}}</ref> On 19 October 2014, Albarn told ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' that he was planning to release new Gorillaz material in 2016.<ref name=\"Kaye, Ben 1\">{{cite magazine | url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/damon-albarn-new-gorillaz-album-coming-in-2016/ | title=Damon Albarn says new Gorillaz album coming in 2016 | magazine=Consequence of Sound | date=19 October 2014 | accessdate=19 October 2014 | author=Kaye, Ben | page=1}}</ref> Albarn has described the music that he has written for the next Gorillaz album as being very upbeat, humorous, and positive, stating that he plans on giving the tracks \"a benchmark of 125 bpm and nothing underneath that\", while also suggesting that it once again may have many collaborations.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Ben|title=Swide|url=http://www.swide.com/art-culture/damon-albarn-music-interview-about-everyday-robots-album-2014-blur-and-tour/2014/06/17|website=Swide.com|accessdate=25 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610173916/http://www.swide.com/art-culture/damon-albarn-music-interview-about-everyday-robots-album-2014-blur-and-tour/2014/06/17|archive-date=10 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lindsay|first1=Cam|title=Damon Albarn in the Spotlight|url=http://exclaim.ca/Music/article/damon_albarn-in_spotlight|work=Exclaim!|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Book|first1=Ryan|title=Damon Albarn Writing A Musical While Flirting with Blur and Gorillaz Comebacks|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/7797/20140721/damon-albarn-writing-musical-flirting-blur-gorillaz-comebacks.htm|work=The Music Times|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> On 16 July 2015, Albarn stated during an interview for ABC's [[7.30]] in Australia that he would begin work on the next Gorillaz album: \"I'm starting recording in September for a new Gorillaz record, I've just been really, really busy so I haven't had a chance. I'd love to just get back in to that routine of being at home and coming to the studio five days a week.\"<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6634331/gorillaz-new-album-2015-damon-albarn \"Damon Albarn: New Gorillaz Album Coming, Recording Starts in September\"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 31 July 2015</ref>\n\nSpeaking about his relationship with Hewlett, Albarn said that the pair's well-publicized fall-out has helped their relationship in the long term.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/gorillaz/88966 |title=New Gorillaz album will be released in 2016, says Jamie Hewlett |work=NME |date=12 October 2015 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> In October 2015, Albarn revealed to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' that he and Hewlett were working on a new Gorillaz album.<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/damon-albarn-on-blurs-big-return-banksy-really-fast-new-gorillaz-lp-20151014?page=2 \"Damon Albarn on Blur's Big Return, Banksy, 'Really Fast' New Gorillaz LP\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915113916/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/damon-albarn-on-blurs-big-return-banksy-really-fast-new-gorillaz-lp-20151014?page=2 |date=15 September 2017 }}. Rolling Stone. Retrieved 25 October 2015</ref> In April 2016, Hewlett uploaded two video clips onto his [[Instagram]] showing the continued work on the album. The first clip featured [[Liam Bailey]] and rumoured executive producer on the album ''The Twilite Tone''. The second clip was a time-lapse video featuring Albarn, Bailey, [[The Twilite Tone]] and [[Jean-Michel Jarre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebanginbeats.com/2016/04/14/virtual-band-gorillaz-teases-their-upcoming-album-with-glimpses-inside-the-studio/ |title=Virtual Band Gorillaz Teases Their Upcoming Album with Glimpses Inside The Studio |first=Surbhi |last=Mittal |date=14 April 2016 |work=thebanginbeats.com |accessdate=23 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625081736/http://thebanginbeats.com/2016/04/14/virtual-band-gorillaz-teases-their-upcoming-album-with-glimpses-inside-the-studio/ |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/gorillaz-phase-4-first-footage-of-jamie-hewlett-and-damon-albarn-in-studio-emerges-online-a6980866.html|title=First footage of Damon Albarn working on new Gorillaz album emerges online|date=12 April 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7326580/gorillaz-jamie-hewlett-studio-videos-new-album-sessions-albarn|title=Gorillaz's Jamie Hewlett Posts In-Studio Videos of New Album Sessions|work=Billboard|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref> On 17 May 2016, Gorillaz were in the studio with Chicago-based hip hop artist [[Vic Mensa]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brennan|first1=Collin|title=Gorillaz hit the studio with Chicago rapper Vic Mensa|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/gorillaz-hit-the-studio-with-chicago-rapper-vic-mensa/|website=Consequenceofsound.net|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/gorillaz/93634|title=Vic Mensa pictured in the studio with Gorillaz|work=NME|last1=Renshaw|first1=David|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mitchell|first1=Chris|title=Vic Mensa spotted in studio with Gorillaz|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.38856/title.vic-mensa-spotted-in-studio-with-gorillaz|website=HipHopDX.com|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=El|title=It was Mensa be: GORILLAZ ARE WORKING WITH VIC MENSA ON THEIR NEW ALBUM|url=https://diymag.com/2016/05/18/gorillaz-recording-with-vic-mensa|website=DIYMag.com|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2016, Gorillaz began an abridged retrospective timeline of the history of Gorillaz releases since 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Monroe|first1=Jazz|title=Gorillaz Launch Instagram Account, Career-Spanning Timeline|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/68410-gorillaz-are-now-on-instagram/|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Harrison|title=GORILLAZ LAUNCH A NEW INSTAGRAM ACCOUNT AND WEBSITE ALLUDING TO THEIR ALBUM|url=http://mixmag.net/read/gorillaz-launch-new-instagram-account-and-website-new-album-coming-soon-news|work=Mixmag|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bein|first1=Kat|title=Gorillaz Launch New Instagram, Website Ahead of Forthcoming Album|url=https://billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7517934/gorillaz-new-instagram-website-2017-album?|work=Billboard|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> On 3 October 2016, Gorillaz began posting a series of interactive multimedia stories revolving around the fictional lives of each Gorillaz character since their hiatus to their social media profiles, beginning with ''The Book of Noodle'' (she ended up in Japan and tracked down a demon crime boss), then ''The Book of Russel'' (he was still a giant from the storyline of Plastic Beach, where he washed up on the shores of North Korea and starved so much he shrank back to normal size), then ''The Book of Murdoc'' (he was captured by the band's record label [[EMI]] at sea and told to make another album), and finishing with ''The Book of 2-D'' (he was swallowed by a whale named Massive Dick on Plastic Beach, and washed up on the shores of Mexico where, to survive, he had to eat the whale's blubber, but it turned out he was just at an empty part of [[Cabo San Lucas]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Alex|title=Gorillaz kick off phase four with The Book of Noodle|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/gorillaz-kick-off-phase-four-with-the-book-of-noodle/|website=ConsequenceofSound.net|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Gorillaz, Brixton Academy, London (34377484273).jpg|thumb|left|Gorillaz (with Albarn to the left) on stage at the [[Brixton Academy]] in London, June 2017]]\nOn 8 October 2016, Noodle was given her own [[Instagram]] page and was announced to be the Global Ambassador of [[Jaguar Racing]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morgan Britton|first1=Luke|title=Watch Gorillaz team up with Jaguar Racing for new short film starring Noodle. |url=https://www.nme.com/news/gorillaz/96954|work=NME|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> On 19 January 2017, a new song from the band entitled \"[[Hallelujah Money]]\" featuring [[Benjamin Clementine]] was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/music/gorillaz-hallelujah-money-video/2/|title=Gorillaz Return After Six Years With Political, Apocalyptic New Video|date=19 January 2017|publisher=uproxx.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/gorillaz-return-their-first-new-song-6-years-halle-248692|title=Gorillaz return with their first new song in 6 years, \"Hallelujah Money\"|date=19 January 2017|access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref> On 6 March, Gorillaz announced the launch of their own festival, called Demon Dayz Festival, which took place on 10 June 2017 at [[Dreamland Margate]] in [[Margate]], Kent, England.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trendell|first1=Andrew|title=Gorillaz announce huge UK comeback show with their own festival at Dreamland, Margate |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/gorillaz-announce-huge-uk-comeback-show-dreamland-margate-2003709|work=NME|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Renshaw|first1=David|title=Gorillaz Has Announced Its Live Return As Part of Their Own Festival|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/03/06/gorillaz-demon-dayz-festival|website=thefader.com|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Alex|title=Gorillaz announce first live performance in five years with launch of their own Demon Dayz festival|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/gorillaz-announce-first-live-performance-in-five-years-with-launch-of-their-own-demon-dayz-festival/|website=Consequenceofsound.net|publisher=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> The band headlined the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indieshuffle.com/news/gorillaz-first-show-since-2010-headlining-demon-dayz-festival/|title=Gorillaz Announce First Show Since 2010 :: Indie Shuffle|website=indieshuffle.com|access-date=7 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2017, the tracklist of the forthcoming album was leaked online, showing guest features from a variety of artists including usual collaborators De La Soul, as well as new collaborators such as [[Grace Jones]], [[Vince Staples]], [[Pusha T]], [[Rag'n'Bone Man]], [[Anthony Hamilton (musician)|Anthony Hamilton]], [[Kilo Kish]] and [[Kali Uchis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tracklist for new Gorillaz album reportedly leaks|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/new-gorillaz-album-tracklist-leaks-2020874|last1=Thomas|first1=Helen|work=[[NME]]|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vince Staples, Danny Brown and more to feature on new Gorillaz album according to leaked tracklist|url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/03/18/vince-staples-danny-brown-feature-new-gorillaz-album-according-leaked-tracklist/|last=Bychawski|first=Adam|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Grace Jones, Kelela, Danny Brown Rumored to Appear on New Gorillaz Album|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/gorillaz-new-album-rumors|last=Julious|first=Britt|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2017, Gorillaz announced via Instagram that the new album will be entitled ''[[Humanz]]'', with a scheduled release date of 28 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1931383/four-new-gorillaz-songs-appear-on-tidal/news/ |title=New Gorillaz Album Humanz Out 4/28 |publisher=[[Stereogum]] |date=23 March 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> On the official Gorillaz YouTube page, two new music videos were released for their track \"[[Saturnz Barz]]\", one of which was in a 360\u00ba view. The track features vocals from Jamaican dancehall artist [[Popcaan]]. The band also released an art video for the track \"[[Andromeda (song)|Andromeda]]\", featuring an animated planet in a galaxy. The track features the American rapper [[DRAM (rapper)|D.R.A.M.]], two more art videos were released: \"[[Ascension (Gorillaz song)|Ascension]]\" (featuring American rapper Vince Staples) and \"[[We Got the Power (Gorillaz song)|We Got the Power]]\" (featuring [[Jehnny Beth]] of the English rock band [[Savages (band)|Savages]] and [[Noel Gallagher]] of [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Damon Albarn talks working with Noel Gallagher on new Gorillaz track 'We Got The Power'|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/damon-albarn-noel-gallagher-gorillaz-we-got-the-power-2026536|work=NME|date=6 April 2017}}</ref> On 6 April 2017, the fifth single from ''Humanz'', \"[[Let Me Out (Gorillaz song)|Let Me Out]]\" (featuring [[Mavis Staples]] and [[Pusha T]]), was released, followed by a performance of the song on ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' on 27 April.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cantor|first1=Brian|title=Gorillaz Perform 'Let Me Out' on Stephen Colbert's \"Late Show\"|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2017/04/27/first-look-gorillaz-perform-thursdays-late-show-stephen-colbert/|website=TV News|accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref> On 10 April 2017, a Gorillaz themed [[augmented reality]] app created in collaboration with [[Electronic Beats]] was released. On 24 April 2017, four days before the ''Humanz'' release date, another promotional single was uploaded, titled \"The Apprentice\". It is the only new song taken from the deluxe edition of ''Humanz''.\n\nOn 28 April 2017, ''Humanz'' was released worldwide. On 8 June 2017, the non-album single \"[[Sleeping Powder]]\" was released, along with an accompanying music video. On 10 June 2017, the band headlined the Demon Dayz Festival in [[Margate]], [[England]]. On 4 August 2017 the band released \"[[Strobelite]]\" as a single with an accompanying music video.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-the-video-for-gorillaz-single-strobelight-2121940 |title = Watch the video for new Gorillaz single \u2018Strobelight\u2019 |date = 7 August 2017 |agency = [[NME]] }}</ref> On 31 October 2017, \"Garage Palace\" was released as a single from the \"Super Deluxe\" Edition of ''Humanz'', which includes 14 additional songs and was released on 3 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-gorillaz-little-simz-slay-foes-in-garage-palace-video-w510734|title=Watch Gorillaz, Little Simz Slay Foes in 'Garage Palace' Video|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/05/gorillazs-humanz-vinyl-box-set-boasts-14-unreleased-bonus-tracks/|title=Gorillaz's Humanz vinyl box set boasts 14 unreleased bonus tracks|date=7 May 2017|publisher=consequenceofsound.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qoAxRICB9j8|title=Gorillaz \u2013 Garage Palace (Visualiser)|last=Gorillaz|date=31 October 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> In December 2017, the band released a ''Humanz''-themed, [[Fictional universe|in-universe]] magazine called G Magazine.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=935490663365468160|user=gorillaz|title=Murdoc Niccals here with an early xmas present for you lucky b*****ds.|author=Gorillaz|date=28 November 2017}}</ref> On 21 February 2018, the band received the [[Brit Award for British Group]] for their work on ''Humanz''. During their acceptance speech, a short-video of Murdoc was played, showing him being imprisoned for an unknown reason.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=966439918347014144|user=gorillaz|title=And now, a message from Murdoc Niccals|author=Gorillaz|date=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Now Now'' (2018\u201319) ===\nIn an interview with ''[[Q Magazine]]'' in September 2017, Albarn hinted at another potential Gorillaz album being in production. He mentioned enjoying the spontaneity of recording and debuting music while on tour, similarly to the band's 2010 release ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]'', but expressed desire to make it a comparatively more \"complete\" record, adding that \"If we're going to do more with Gorillaz we don't want to wait seven years because, y'know, we're getting on a bit now\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Gorillaz might drop a surprise album on us|url=http://mixmag.net/read/the-gorillaz-might-drop-a-surprise-new-album-on-us-news|website=Mixmag|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> At the end of the same month on 30 September 2017 while touring for ''[[Humanz]]'', the band debuted a new song in Seattle called \"Idaho\". Hewlett confirmed later on in December 2017 that the band planned to release a follow-up album to ''Humanz'' in 2018, citing a desire to keep the band going rather than take any prolonged breaks as the band had usually done with previous projects. Hewlett described several of the demos and new material as a \"new direction\" for the band, stating that he hopes to move the band's artwork in a similar direction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jamie Hewlett says Gorillaz will release a new album next year|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/12/jamie-hewlett-says-gorillaz-will-release-a-new-album-next-year/|website=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> During a performance in Chile on the final leg of the [[Humanz Tour]], Albarn confirmed that the new album was coming \"very soon\" and premiered a new song called \"[[Hollywood (Gorillaz song)|Hollywood]]\" featuring [[Jamie Principle]] and [[Snoop Dogg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/twitter/statuses/976522747030462464|title=Damon Albarn on Twitter|website=Twitter|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> On 26 May 2018, the album was officially announced to be titled ''[[The Now Now]]'', being co-produced by [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qobuz.com/gb-en/album/the-now-now-gorillaz/gopjozt6bd9wc|title=The Now Now {{!}} Gorillaz \u2013 Download and listen to the album|website=[[Qobuz]]|quote=Display track details|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Alex|title=Gorillaz tease new album, The Now Now, due out in June|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/05/gorillaz-tease-new-album/|accessdate=27 May 2018|website=Consequence of Sound|date=26 May 2018}}</ref> On 31 May, the music video for the single \"[[Humility (song)|Humility]]\" featuring [[George Benson]], was released alongside \"Lake Zurich\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Gorillaz Detail New Album, Announce Tour, Release Two New Songs|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/gorillaz-share-new-song-humility-listen/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=21 May 2018}}</ref> From 7 to 21 June, the band released the singles \"Sorcererz\", \"Fire Flies\", and \"Hollywood\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Gorillaz Debut New Songs Live, Share \"Sorcererz\": Listen|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-gorillaz-debut-4-new-songs-live/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=7 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to Gorillaz\u2019s New Song \"Fire Flies\"|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-gorillazs-new-song-fire-flies/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=14 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gorillaz Link Up With Snoop Dogg on New Song \"Hollywood\": Listen|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/gorillaz-link-up-with-snoop-dogg-on-new-song-hollywood-listen/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=21 June 2018}}</ref> ''The Now Now'' was released on 29 June 2018. On 13 September, \"[[Tranz]]\" was released as a single along with a music video.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Gorillaz' New \"Tranz\" Video\"|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-gorillazs-new-tranz-video/|accessdate=14 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=13 September 2018}}</ref> All of the songs from the album have a visualizer except \"Humility\".\n\nIn the fictional Gorillaz storyline, the band introduced [[Ace (The Powerpuff Girls)|Ace]] from [[Cartoon Network]]'s animated series ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'' as a temporary bassist of the band, filling in for the imprisoned Murdoc Niccals (as seen in the band's [[Brit Awards]] acceptance speech for ''Humanz'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/the-gorillaz-ace-powerpuff-girls/|title=The Gorillaz's New Band Member is a Powerpuff Girls Character|date=31 May 2018|website=Cbr.com|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> From 4 June to 26 October 2018, the band ran a bi-weekly [[Interactive fiction|text-adventure]] [[Alternate reality game|ARG]] called ''\"Free Murdoc\"'', in which the player assists Murdoc as he attempts to escape from prison.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1003672759917039616|user=MurdocGorillaz|title=SOS, I need your help! PRONTO. So, here\u2019s what I need you to do.. |author=Murdoc Niccals|date=4 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1011295575784984576|user=gorillaz|title=Pick your side. Murdoc fans this way|author=Gorillaz|date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nme.com/music-interviews/gorillaz-exclusive-murdoc-hits-back-2d-wormwood-scrubs-cell-2354976 |title = Gorillaz: Murdoc hits back at 2D in exclusive prison interview |date = 17 July 2018 |agency = [[NME]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1056108490769514497|user=gorillaz|title=WHO WANTS TO TALK TO UNCLE MURDOC, EH? YOU\u2019VE GOT 5 MORE HOURS!|author=Gorillaz|date=27 October 2018}}</ref> Murdoc was reunited with the band on 20 September, in time to join them on the final leg of [[The Now Now Tour]].<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1042749783205662721|user=gorillaz|title=Murdoc. He's back. In the nick of time|author=Gorillaz|date=20 September 2018}}</ref> On 25 October, the band announced they would be partnering with [[G-Shock]] to create a line of Gorillaz watches.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1055463449373880321|user=gorillaz|title=Gorillaz x G Shock: pre-order now at|author=Gorillaz|date=25 October 2018}}</ref> To promote the watches, the band released a monthly web-series called ''Mission M101''.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1042776403882766336|user=gorillaz|title=G-TIME is NOW! Part 1|author=Gorillaz|date=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1055458968494096384|user=gorillaz|title=G-TIME is NOW! Watch episode 2|author=Gorillaz|date=25 October 2018}}</ref> On 21 November 2019, the band announced a documentary covering the production of ''Humanz'' and ''The Now Now'' and their accompanying tours titled ''Gorillaz: Reject False Icons''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strauss |first1=Matthew |title=Gorillaz Announce New Movie Reject False Icons |url= https://pitchfork.com/news/gorillaz-announce-new-movie-reject-false-icons/ |publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=21 November 2019 |date=21 November 2019}}</ref> It was released on 16 December via a worldwide theatrical screening.<ref name=\"clash\">{{cite web |author1=Clash Music |title=Five Things We Learned From New Gorillaz Film Reject False Icons |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/five-things-we-learned-from-new-gorillaz-film-reject-false-icons |publisher=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]] |accessdate=16 December 2019 |date=16 December 2019}}</ref> Eight days later, an edited version of the documentary subtitled the \"Director's Cut\" was uploaded through the Gorillaz official YouTube page in three parts: ''Humanz'',<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vccKwyv4qxE|title=GORILLAZ: REJECT FALSE ICONS {{!}} Act One - Humanz (Director's Cut)|via=YouTube|publisher=Gorillaz|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> ''Humanz World Tour''<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zWlP1MeRkN8|title=GORILLAZ: REJECT FALSE ICONS {{!}} Act Two - Humanz World Tour (Director's Cut)|via=YouTube|publisher=Gorillaz|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> and ''The Now Now''.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qGKgMuYKqf4|title=GORILLAZ: REJECT FALSE ICONS {{!}} Act Three - The Now Now (Director's Cut)|via=YouTube|publisher=Gorillaz|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Song Machine'' (2020\u2013present) ===\nOn 28 January 2020, the band officially released images via social media teasing a concept entitled ''[[Song Machine]]''.  A 23-second promotional track entitled \"Song Machine Theme Tune\" was released on streaming services with an accompanying video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2071709/gorillaz-song-machine-season-one-tease/news/|title=Gorillaz Are Teasing Something Called 'Song Machine'|date=2020-01-28|website=Stereogum|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> The following day, further information was released regarding the project, revealing that new \"episodes\" would be released spontaneously throughout the year. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/gorillaz-new-music-video-series-song-machine-details-944519/|title=Gorillaz Detail New Music, Video Series 'Song Machine'|last=Blistein|first=Jon|last2=Blistein|first2=Jon|date=2020-01-29|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> Each episode featured previously unannounced guest musicians on new Gorillaz material, with the first being \"[[Momentary Bliss]]\", which was released on 31 January and features both British rapper [[Slowthai|Slowthai]] and the [[Kent]]-based punk rock duo [[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nastylittleman.com/artists/gorillaz/|title=GORILLAZ {{!}} Nasty Little Man|website=www.nastylittleman.com|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\nUpon the premiere of \"Momentary Bliss\", Albarn revealed that the group had been in the studio with [[ScHoolboy Q]] and [[Sampa the Great]] among others, although he did say that these songs were likely to be saved for future series of ''Song Machine''.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/m000drwj</ref> The group also teased a possible collaboration with Australian band [[Tame Impala]] on [[Instagram]].<ref>https://www.nme.com/news/music/gorillaz-tease-tame-impala-collaboration-as-song-machine-project-continues-2603985</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, the band released the second episode of ''Song Machine'' entitled \"[[D\u00e9sol\u00e9]]\". The song features [[Mali|Malian]] singer [[Fatoumata Diawara]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blistein |first1=Jon |title=Gorillaz Team With Malian Star Fatoumata Diawara for New Song \u2018D\u00e9sol\u00e9\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/gorillaz-fatoumata-diawara-new-song-desole-song-machine-958067/ |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=27 February 2020 |date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Style ==\nWriters and critics have variously described Gorillaz as [[art pop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as art pop:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/11/gorillaz-review-dreamland|title=Gorillaz review \u2013 Albarn's Demon Dayz festival brings joyful apocalypse to the pier|last=Wright|first=Danny|work=The Guardian|date=1 June 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1930553/leaked-gorillaz-demos-support-rumored-new-album-tracklist/news/|title=Leaked Gorillaz Demos Support Rumored New Album Tracklist|last=Breihan|first=Tom|publisher=Stereogum|date=20 March 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/07622-gorillaz-the-singles-collection-2001-2011-review|title=Gorillaz |last=Calvert|first=John|magazine=The Quietus|date=23 December 2011|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/504508/gorillazjames-murphyandre-3000s-converse-track-the-story-behind-the-song|title=Gorillaz/James Murphy/Andre 3000's Converse Track: The Story Behind The Song|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|work=Billboard|date=21 February 2012|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/music-gorillaz-in-our-midst/104900124/|title=Music: Gorillaz in our midst|last=Boller|first=Jay|work=Star Tribune|date=17 August 2012|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|title=Leaked Gorillaz Demos Support Rumored New Album Tracklist|work=[[Yahoo Entertainment]]|first=Tom|last=Breihan|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/leaked-gorillaz-demos-support-rumored-085034988.html|quote=\"the return of Damon Albarn\u2019s beloved art-pop project Gorillaz\"|date=20 March 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}\n*{{cite web|title=Benjamin Clementine Biography|work=[[Allmusic]]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/benjamin-clementine-mn0003277471/biography|quote=\"Damon Albarn and Jamie Hewlett's art-pop project Gorillaz's fourth album, Humanz.\"|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[alternative rock]],<ref>The following references cite the band as alternative rock:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/gorillaz-plan-escape-to-plastic-beach-world-tour-2033956.html|title=Gorillaz plan \"Escape to Plastic Beach\" world tour|work=[[The Independent]]|first=|last=|date=|accessdate=10 November 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/gorillaz-update-us-what-russels-been-too-243889|title=Gorillaz update us on what Russel's been up to, too|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|first=William|last=Hughes|accessdate=14 May 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://vrscout.com/news/watch-gorillaz-360-music-video-vr-headset|title=How To Watch The Gorillaz 360\u00b0 Music Video on Any VR Headset \u2013 VRScout|date=28 March 2017|publisher=vrscout.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/new-gorillaz-music-due-for-release-in-2016/|title=New Gorillaz Music Due For Release In 2016 \u2013 Music Feeds|date=13 October 2015|website=Musicfeeds.com|accessdate=29 June 2018}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/78wbq9/a-list-of-bands-youre-not-allowed-to-like-anymore-since-alternative-became-a-bad-word|title=A List of Bands You're Not Allowed to Like Anymore Since \"Alternative\" Became a Bad Word|date=27 January 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/gorillaz-contributors-and-discography|title=Inside the Gorillaverse: A Look at Alt-Rock's Best Cartoon Band|website=Metacritic}}</ref> [[hip hop music|hip hop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as hip hop:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/may/13/popandrock.shopping3|title=Gorillaz, Demon Days|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|work=The Guardian|date=13 May 2005|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/album/gorillaz-human/|title=Gorillaz \u2013 'Humanz'|last=Wehner|first=Cyclone|magazine=Music Feeds|date=April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://districtmagazine.ie/the-10-best-gorillaz-collaborations-with-hip-hop-artists/|title=The 10 best Gorillaz collaborations with hip hop artists|last=Davidson|first=Eric|publisher=District|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[Pop music|pop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as pop:\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/07622-gorillaz-the-singles-collection-2001-2011-review|title=Gorillaz |last=Calvert|first=John|magazine=The Quietus|date=23 December 2011|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite book |last = Brown |first = Cass |authorlink = Cass Browne |author2=Gorillaz |title = [[Rise of the Ogre]] |date = 2 November 2006 |publisher = Penguin |location = United States |isbn = 1-59448-931-9 |pages = 43\u20137 }}\n*{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/04/gorillaz-in-10-songs/|title=Gorillaz in 10 Songs|last=Phillips|first=Lior|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[trip hop]],<ref>The following references describe the band as trip hop:\n*{{cite web|last1=Lynch|first1=Joe|title=The Week's Best New Music: Feist, Gorillaz, Mary J. Blige & More|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7776267/best-new-music-feist-gorillaz-mary-j-blige|work=Billboard|accessdate=14 May 2017}}\n*{{cite news |first= Kieran |last= Grant |title= Gorillaz in his midst |date= 20 January 2001 |publisher= Jam! |accessdate= 12 July 2016 |url= http://jam.canoe.com/Music/Artists/B/Blur/2001/01/20/pf-743419.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304191554/http://jam.canoe.com/Music/Artists/B/Blur/2001/01/20/pf-743419.html |archivedate= 4 March 2016 |df= dmy-all }}\n*{{cite news|first=Lisa |last=Lee |title=Miho Hatori Uses Her Noodle |date=1 June 2007 |newspaper=[[AsianWeek]] |url=http://www.asianweek.com/2007/06/01/miho-hatori-uses-her-noodle/ |accessdate=12 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704190236/http://www.asianweek.com/2007/06/01/miho-hatori-uses-her-noodle/ |archivedate=4 July 2015 |df= }}</ref> [[dark pop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as dark pop:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/top-ten-damon-albarn-albums|title=A 10 Album Introduction To Damon Albarn|date=5 October 2016|website=Theodysseyonline.com|accessdate=29 June 2018}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.vblurpage.com/news/2005/0407.htm|title=Blur News \u2013 Damon talks about \"Demon Days\" and his future projects \u2013 Apr 7, 2005|publisher=}}</ref> [[alternative hip hop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as alternative hip hop or alternative rap:\n*{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/78wbq9/a-list-of-bands-youre-not-allowed-to-like-anymore-since-alternative-became-a-bad-word|title=A List of Bands You're Not Allowed to Like Anymore Since \"Alternative\" Became a Bad Word|date=27 January 2017}}\n*{{cite web|last1=DeGroot|first1=Joey|title=Gorillaz Co-Creator Jamie Hewlett Preps Retrospective Art Book|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/18527/20141203/gorillaz-jamie-hewlett-damon-albarn-preps-retrospective-art-book.htm|work=Music Times|accessdate=4 December 2014|page=1|quote=\"In other Gorillaz news, Damon Albarn recently revealed plans to revive the beloved alternative hip-hop outfit, telling ''The Sydney Morning Herald'' that he intends on releasing a new Gorillaz album in 2016.\"}}</ref> [[rap rock]],<ref>The following references cite the band as rap rock:\n*{{cite web|last=Hermes |first=Will |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-gorillaz-humanz-rings-in-the-apocalypse-in-style-w478893 |title=Review: Gorillaz' 'Humanz' Rings in the Apocalypse in Style |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=27 April 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}\n*{{cite web|author=Sean Palmer |url=http://www.queanbeyanagechronicle.com.au/story/4646118/gorillaz-in-the-midst-of-rap-rock/?cs=5355 |title=Gorillaz in the midst of rap-rock &#124; The Queanbeyan Age |website=Queanbeyanagechronicle.com.au |date=8 May 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> [[indie rock]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diffuser.fm/10-best-gorillaz-songs/|title=10 Best Gorillaz Songs|website=Diffuser.fm|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> [[electronica]],<ref name=\"mfHZ\">{{cite magazine|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/album/gorillaz-human/|title=Gorillaz \u2013 'Humanz'|last=Wehner|first=Cyclone|magazine=Music Feeds|date=April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[bedroom pop]],<ref>https://www.popmatters.com/gorillaz-the-now-now-2583303134.amp.html</ref> [[dance-rock]],<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-singles-collection-2001-2011-mw0002241721 \"The Singles Collection 2001\u20132011\"]. AllMusic. Retrieved 19 November 2014</ref> [[new wave music|new wave]],<ref name=\"cosHZ\">{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/04/gorillaz-in-10-songs/|title=Gorillaz in 10 Songs|last=Phillips|first=Lior|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[funk music|funk]]<ref name=\"cosHZ\" /> and [[worldbeat]].<ref name=\"mfHZ\" /> The band's aesthetic and general approach has been described as [[postmodern]].<ref name=\"mfHZ\" /> According to ''[[AllMusic]]'' Gorillaz blend [[Britpop]] and hip-hop,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/gorillaz-mn0000664770|title=Gorillaz \u2013 Biography, Albums, Streaming Links|website=AllMusic|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> while ''[[The Guardian]]'' described the band as \"a sort of [[dub music|dub]]/hip-hop/[[lo-fi music|lo-fi]] indie/[[world music]] hybrid\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/may/13/popandrock.shopping3|title=Gorillaz, Demon Days|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|work=The Guardian|date=13 May 2005|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> According to ''[[PopMatters]]'', the band's early work foreshadowed \"the melding of hip-hop, rock, and [[electronic music|electronic]] elements in pop music\" that grew in significance in the next decade.<ref name=\"pm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/121872-gorillaz-plastic-beach-2496174715.html|title=Gorillaz: Plastic Beach|last=Kabran|first=Michael|website=PopMatters|date=7 March 2010|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Live performances ==\n[[File:Apollo Marquee 2006.jpg|thumb|right|Gorillaz performed ''Demon Days'' at the [[Apollo Theater]] in Harlem, New York in April 2006.]]\nIn March 2001, Gorillaz played their first show at the [[Scala (club)|Scala]] in London before embarking on a tour later that summer, with one date in Paris and two in Japan. The show, called [[Gorillaz Live]], saw the live band playing behind a giant projector screen which covered the whole stage, on which was projected various visuals and images created by Hewlett. After taking a short break over the holidays, the tour resumed with a North American leg in February 2002.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/77222/gorillaz-plan-animated-north-american-tour \"Gorillaz plan animated North American tour\"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 30 July 2015</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, Gorillaz performed [[Demon Days Live]], a five night residency at the [[Manchester Opera House]] in Manchester, England in which the album ''[[Demon Days]]'' was presented in its entirety. The event was filmed by an EMI film crew for a DVD release, ''[[Demon Days Live]]'', in late March 2006. It was later announced that an American version of the event would take place in April 2006 at the [[Apollo Theater]] in [[Harlem]], New York. Within an hour of release tickets were sold out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0634.php#060314 |title=NYC Sellout/GES Competition |accessdate=7 January 2007 |date=14 March 2006 |work=fans.gorillaz.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627153053/http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0634.php#060314 |archivedate=27 June 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The show of 6 April was filmed for a live [[webcast]] at [[MSN Video]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/press/2006/apr06/04-04GorillazWebcastPR.mspx |title=MSN Video to Stream Exclusive Live Broadcast of GORILLAZ 'DEMON DAYS LIVE' Concert From the Apollo Theater |accessdate=7 January 2007 |date=5 April 2006 |publisher=[[Microsoft]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404201739/http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/press/2006/apr06/04-04GorillazWebcastPR.mspx |archivedate=4 April 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Palladia]] (then known as MHD) also broadcast an Apollo Theater show in [[High-definition television|HDTV]] on 31 December 2006.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-156045603.html |title = MTV Networks' MHD: Music High-Definition Rings in the New Year With Exclusive Premiere of 'Gorillaz: Live in Harlem' Concert in High-Def |accessdate =7 January 2007 |date = 19 December 2006 |agency = [[PR Newswire]] }}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n[[File:Gorillaz live 2010.jpg|thumb|Gorillaz performing at the [[Roundhouse (venue)|Roundhouse]] in London, April 2010|upright=1.25|left]]\n\n\nIn March 2010, Gorillaz began a short six date tour as \"rehearsal\" shows for their headlining slot at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]]. The shows were open exclusively to Gorillaz Sub Division fan club members and featured no visuals whatsoever. These performances were the band's first public performances in four years. Gorillaz headlined the final night of the [[Coachella Festival]] on 18 April 2010 as their first proper, full show. On 27 April they were the main guests on ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'' on the BBC. In addition, Gorillaz played a two-night residency at London's Camden Roundhouse (29 and 30 April 2010). [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] and [[Paul Simonon]] of [[the Clash]] performed guitar and bass respectively with the band and more than once in the evening chords from the Clash song \"[[Guns of Brixton]]\" were heard as a subtle reference to their presence.<ref>T\u00e9l\u00e9moustique 5 May 2010, page 59, Roundhouse concert review by Luc Lorf\u00e8vre</ref>\n[[File:Gorillaz at Oslo Spektrum 2.jpg|thumb|right|Gorillaz at the [[Oslo Spektrum]] in November 2017]]\n\nGorillaz embarked on the [[Escape to Plastic Beach Tour]] in October 2010, with some concerts preceding festival dates in the summer, such as at the Byblos Festival in Lebanon, the [[Roskilde Festival]] in Denmark, headlining the [[Glastonbury Festival]] in England and one show at the [[Citadel of Damascus]] in Syria.<ref>{{cite news |title = Gorillaz perform one-off show in Syria |first = Duncan |last = Crawford |publisher = BBC |date = 26 July 2010 |url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/10758917 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Arabian heights: Gorillaz stage historic gig in Syria |first = Stephen |last = Starr |newspaper = The Guardian |date = 27 July 2010 |url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/27/gorillaz-historic-gig-syria }}</ref> The tour took them across North America in October, Europe in November, and finally through Australia, New Zealand, and with one date in Hong Kong in December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorillaz will be playing in Beirut and Syria! |author=Gorillaz Official Website |work=gorillaz.com |date=29 June 2010 |url=http://gorillaz.com/news/news/gorillaz-will-be-playing-in-beirut-and-syria |accessdate=30 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701233141/http://gorillaz.com/news/news/gorillaz-will-be-playing-in-beirut-and-syria |archivedate=1 July 2010 |df= }}</ref> During the final show of the tour at the [[Vector Arena]] in [[Auckland]], New Zealand on 21 December 2010, Albarn announced that it would be their final show with the ''[[Plastic Beach]]'' line up.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jason|last=Gregory|url= http://www.gigwise.com/news/60328/Damon-Albarn-Plays-Final-Gig-With-Gorillaz|title=Damon Albarn Plays 'Final Gig' With Gorillaz|work=Gigwise|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 July 2017, Gorillaz embarked upon the [[Humanz Tour]], the band's second world tour and first since 2010. With 53 scheduled shows and lasting over a year, it was Gorillaz' longest tour in their history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7760521/gorillaz-tour-dates-2017|title=Gorillaz Announce 'Humanz' Tour Dates, Join Life Is Beautiful Festival 2017 Lineup|work=Billboard|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> On 6 December, Gorillaz announced they would be playing [[Boomtown Fair]] as an \"exclusive one-off UK show\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/gorillaz-perform-exclusive-one-uk-14002389 |title=Gorillaz to perform at Boomtown Fair in one-off UK show |last=Nightingale |first=Laura |date=6 December 2017 |website=getsurrey |access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref> After 53 performances, on 30 March 2018, Humanz Tour concluded in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=980798004444712960|user=gorillaz|title=Final momentz of the #HUMANZWORLDTOUR|author=Gorillaz|date=2 April 2018}}</ref> The tour was followed almost immediately by [[The Now Now Tour]], starting in June 2018 in [[Nuremberg]], [[Germany]]. On 20 October, Gorillaz played \"[[Song 2]]\" by [[Blur (band)|Blur]], at the Demon Dayz Festival, with [[Graham Coxon]], in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-gorillaz-bring-out-blurs-graham-coxon-to-perform-song-2/|title=Watch Gorillaz Bring Out Blur\u2019s Graham Coxon to Perform \"Song 2\"|date=21 October 2018|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=24 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> After 29 performances, on 24 October, The Now Now Tour concluded, in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1032275042040594439|user=gorillaz|title=#TheNowNow Tour is coming to Mexico|author=Gorillaz|date=22 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/05/gorillaz-north-american-arena-show-festival/|title=Gorillaz announce North American arena tour, Los Angeles Demon Dayz Festival|date=31 May 2018|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=1 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The Now Now Tour had participations of [[The Internet (band)|The Internet]] and [[Little Dragon]].\n\n== Members ==\n{{For|members only in tours|Gorillaz Live|Demon Days Live|Escape to Plastic Beach Tour|Humanz Tour|The Now Now Tour}}\nThis list includes accredited members in the staff lines of each album, does not include: featurings, remixers, mastering, artwork and assistance.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Permanent members'''\n* [[Damon Albarn]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, instrumentation, songwriting, director <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Jamie Hewlett]]&nbsp;\u2013 artwork, [[VJing|visuals]], [[Special effect|FX]], songwriting, video direction <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Current real musicians'''\n* Stephen Sedgwick&nbsp;\u2013 mixing, engineering <small>(2005\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Remi Kabaka Jr.]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming, mixing, engineering <small>(2011\u2013present)</small>\n* Samuel Egglenton&nbsp;\u2013 mixing, engineering <small>(2017\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Former real musicians'''\n* [[Dan the Automator]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming, songwriting, synthesizers <small>(2001)</small>\n* Tom Girling&nbsp;\u2013 drum programming, mixing, engineering, [[Pro Tools]] <small>(2001)</small>\n* [[Kid Koala]]&nbsp;\u2013 turntables <small>(2001)</small>\n* Toby Whelan&nbsp;\u2013 mixing, engineering <small>(2001)</small>\n* [[Cass Browne]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming <small>(2001\u201305)</small>\n* Jason Cox&nbsp;\u2013 drum programming, additional guitars and bass, mixing, engineering <small>(2001\u201310)</small>\n* Junior Dan&nbsp;\u2013 bass <small>(2001, \"Sorcererz\" (2018))</small>\n* [[Morgan Nicholls]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass <small>(2005)</small>\n* [[Danger Mouse (musician)|Danger Mouse]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming <small>(2005\u201307)</small>\n* James Dring&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming <small>(2005\u201307)</small>\n* [[Simon Tong]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitars <small>(2005\u201310)</small>\n* Rosie Wilson&nbsp;\u2013 additional voices <small>(\"[[Dare (song)|Dare]]\" (2005); \"[[Andromeda (song)|Andromeda]]\" (2017))</small> \n* Gabrielle Wallace&nbsp;\u2013 percussion <small>(2010)</small>\n* [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]]&nbsp;\u2013 additional guitars <small>(2010\u201311)</small>\n* [[Paul Simonon]]&nbsp;\u2013 additional guitars and bass <small>(2010\u201311)</small>\n* [[Jean-Michel Jarre]]&nbsp;\u2013 additional synthesizers <small>(2017)</small>\n* [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, bass, guitar, synthesisers <small>(2018; \"[[D\u00e9sol\u00e9]]\" (2020))</small>\n\n'''Former choirs'''\n* San Fernandez Youth Chorus&nbsp;<small>(2005)</small>{{ref|d}}\n* [[London Community Gospel Choir]]&nbsp;<small>(2005)</small>{{ref|e}}\n* The Humanz&nbsp;<small>(2017)</small>{{ref|b}}\n\n{{col-2}}\n<big>'''Virtual'''</big><br>\n'''Virtual members'''\n* [[Murdoc Niccals]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass, drum programming, occasionally vocals <small>(1998\u20132018; 2018-present){{ref|a}}</small>\n* [[2-D (character)|2-D]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, keyboards, melodica, occasionally rhythm and acoustic guitar <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Russel Hobbs]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming <small>(1998\u20132006; 2012\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitars,{{ref|c}} keyboards, melodica, occasionally vocals <small>(2000\u201305; 2010\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Former virtual members'''\n* Paula Cracker&nbsp;\u2013 lead guitar <small>(1998\u20132000)</small>\n* Cyborg Noodle&nbsp;\u2013 lead and acoustic guitar, keyboards <small>(2008\u201310)</small>\n* [[Ace (The Powerpuff Girls)|Ace]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass <small>(2018)</small>\n\n'''Current character voices'''\n* [[Phil Cornwell]]&nbsp;\u2013 Murdoc Niccals <small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Kevin Bishop]]&nbsp;\u2013 2-D <small>(2017\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Haruka Abe]]&nbsp;\u2013 Noodle <small>(2018\u2013present)</small>\n* Remi Kabaka Jr.&nbsp;\u2013 Russel Hobbs <small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Former character voices'''\n* Nelson De Freitas&nbsp;\u2013 2-D <small>(2000\u201317)</small>\n* [[Haruka Kuroda]]&nbsp;\u2013 Noodle <small>(2000\u201317)</small>\n\n'''Singing voices'''\n* Damon Albarn&nbsp;\u2013 2-D <small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Miho Hatori]]&nbsp;\u2013 Noodle <small>(2001)</small>\n* Rosie Wilson&nbsp;\u2013 Noodle <small>(2005)</small> {{col-end}}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Gorillaz discography}}\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Gorillaz (album)|Gorillaz]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Demon Days]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Plastic Beach]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Humanz]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[The Now Now]]'' (2018)\n\n'''Miscellaneous''' \n* ''[[Song Machine]]'' (2020-present)\n\n== Tours ==\n* [[Gorillaz Live]] (2001\u201302)\n* [[Demon Days Live]] (2005\u201306)\n* [[Escape to Plastic Beach Tour]] (2010)\n* [[Humanz Tour]] (2017\u201318)\n* [[The Now Now Tour]] (2018)\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Gorillaz}}\n\n== Notes ==\n:1.{{note|d}}A children group choir. They toured with the band in some live performances in the [[Demon Days Live]].\n:2.{{note|e}}Featuring: Bazil Meade, Daniel Thomas, Yvonne White, Samantha Smith. They toured with the band in the Demon Days Live.\n:3.{{note|b}}Featuring: Rasul Al-Salaam, Starr Busby, Melanie J-B Charles, Drea D'Nur, Giovanni James, Marcus Anthony Johnson, Janelle Kroll, Brandon Markell-Holmes, Imani Vonsh\u00e0. They toured with the band in the [[Humanz Tour]], and [[The Now Now Tour]].\n:4.{{note|a}}On 21 February 2018, [[Murdoc Niccals|Murdoc]] was in jail during the course of ''[[The Now Now]]''. \n:5.{{note|c}}Lead guitar, acoustic guitar, electric guitar and rhythm guitar.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Sisterlinks|d=Q189991|c=category:Gorillaz|n=no|b=no|v=no|wikt=no|s=no|m=no|mw=no|q=no|species=no}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Curlie|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/G/Gorillaz/}}\n\n{{Gorillaz}}{{Damon Albarn}}\n{{Brit British Group}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Gorillaz \u2013 links to related articles|state=collapsed|list=\n{{Blur}}\n{{The Good, the Bad & the Queen}}\n{{The Clash}}\n{{Del the Funky Homosapien}}}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Gorillaz| ]]\n[[Category:Animated musical groups]]\n[[Category:Recorded music characters]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1998]]\n[[Category:English electronic music groups]]\n[[Category:Electronica music groups]]\n[[Category:Trip hop groups]]\n[[Category:English alternative rock groups]]\n[[Category:English indie rock groups]]\n[[Category:Dance-rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:English hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Rap rock groups]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:English pop music groups]]\n[[Category:British world music groups]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:Parlophone artists]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records artists]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Bands with fictional stage personas]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the album|Gorillaz (album)}}\n{{short description|British virtual band}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Gorillaz\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Gorillaz band photo.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = From left to right: [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]], [[Murdoc Niccals|Murdoc]], [[2-D (character)|2-D]], [[Russel Hobbs|Russel]]\n| origin           = [[Westbourne Grove]], [[London]], England\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[art pop]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n* {{nowrap|[[trip hop]]}}\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n<!--Please do not add every applicable sub-genre, Template:Infobox musical artist states it should \"aim for generality\".-->\n}}\n| years_active     = 1998\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Parlophone]]\n* [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n* [[Warner Records|Warner]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|<!-- Per Template:Infobox_musical_artist#associated_acts: \"The following uses of this field should be avoided: [...] Groups with only one member in common / One-time collaboration for a single song / Groups that have played or toured together as separate acts / Groups that are merely similar\" -->\n* [[Blur (band)|Blur]]\n* [[The Good, the Bad & the Queen]]\n* [[Monkey: Journey to the West]]\n* [[Spacemonkeyz]]\n* [[Del the Funky Homosapien]]\n* [[De La Soul]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]\n* [[Bobby Womack]]\n* [[Mos Def]]\n* [[Fatoumata Diawara]]\n* [[The Clash]]\n* [[Senseless Things]]\n}}\n| website          = {{url|Gorillaz.com}}\n| current_members  = '''Non-virtual:'''<br>[[Damon Albarn]]<br>[[Jamie Hewlett]]<br>[[Remi Kabaka Jr.]]<br>'''Virtual:'''<br>[[2-D (character)|2-D]]<br>[[Murdoc Niccals]]<br>[[Russel Hobbs]]<br>[[Noodle (character)|Noodle]]\n| past_members     = '''Virtual:'''<br>Paula Cracker<br>Cyborg Noodle<br>[[Ace (The Powerpuff Girls)|Ace]]\n}}\n'''Gorillaz''' are <!--This article is written in British English, which treats collective nouns plural, Do not change \"are\" to \"is\". Too, don't remove \"British virtual band\" to \"English virtual band\".--> a British [[virtual band]] created in 1998 by [[Damon Albarn]] and artist [[Jamie Hewlett]]. The band primarily consists of four animated members: [[2-D (character)|Stuart \"2-D\" Pot]], [[Murdoc Niccals]], [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]], and [[Russel Hobbs]]. Their [[fictional universe]] is presented in music videos, interviews and short cartoons. In reality, Albarn is the only permanent musical contributor, and he often collaborates with other musicians.  [[Remi Kabaka Jr.]] became producer for the band in 2016 after several years providing the voice of [[Russel Hobbs]] and was listed as an official member alongside Albarn and Hewlett in the 2019 Gorillaz documentary ''Gorillaz: Reject False Icons''.<ref>{{cite AV media |last=Hewlett |first=Denholm |date=24 December 2019 |title=Gorillaz: Reject False Icons (Director's Cut) |medium=Motion picture |url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=qGKgMuYKqf4 |access-date=5 January 2020 |time=23:32 |location=YouTube |publisher=Gorillaz}}</ref> \n\nWith Gorillaz, Albarn departed from the distinct [[Britpop]] of his band [[Blur (band)|Blur]] through [[hip hop]], [[electronic music]], and [[world music]] through an \"eccentrically [[postmodern]]\" approach.<ref name=\"mfHZ\" /> The band's 2001 debut album ''[[Gorillaz (album)|Gorillaz]]'' went triple platinum in the UK and double platinum in Europe and earned the group an entry in the ''[[Guinness World Records|Guinness Book of World Records]]'' as the Most Successful Virtual Band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inthenews.co.uk/entertainment/reviews/music/r-n-b-rap/gorillaz-d-sides-$1170827.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418193200/http://www.inthenews.co.uk/entertainment/reviews/music/r-n-b-rap/gorillaz-d-sides-$1170827.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 April 2010|title=WebCite query result|website=www.webcitation.org|language=en|access-date=6 July 2018}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Mercury Prize]], but the nomination was withdrawn at the band's request.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1454491.stm|title=Mercury Music Prize: The nominees|accessdate=7 September 2007|date=25 July 2001|work=[[BBC News]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124123736/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1454491.stm|archivedate=24 November 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> Their second studio album, ''[[Demon Days]]'' (2005), went six times platinum in the UK<ref name=\"Platinum UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|title=Certified Awards Search|accessdate=17 January 2010|date=24 February 2006|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] <!-- Search for \"Gorillaz\" -->|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704041118/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx|archivedate=4 July 2011}}</ref> and [[Music recording sales certification|double platinum]] in the US.<ref name=\"Platinum US\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Gorillaz&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50 |title=Gorillaz RIAA certifications |accessdate=7 December 2008 |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903230335/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Gorillaz&format=ALBUM&go=Search&perPage=50 |archivedate=3 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=2006grammynomination>{{cite news|url=http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2005/Press35.htm|title=EMI Music earns 54 Grammy nominations|accessdate=1 June 2007|date=8 December 2005|publisher=[[EMI]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090508024333/http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2005/Press35.htm|archivedate=8 May 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.emimusicpub.com/news/emi-music-publishing-wins-big-at-the-grammys!.php|title=EMI Music Publishing Wins Big at the Grammys!|accessdate=17 January 2010|date=14 February 2006|publisher=[[EMI]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929161637/http://emimusicpub.com/news/emi-music-publishing-wins-big-at-the-grammys!.php|archivedate=29 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe third Gorillaz studio album, ''[[Plastic Beach]]'', was released on 3 March 2010. The fourth, ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]'', was released on 25 December 2010 as a surprise gift for paying fan club members, then on 18 April 2011 as an official release. The fifth, ''[[Humanz]]'', was released after a six-year hiatus on 28 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/61678-gorillaz-announce-new-album-humanz-featuring-grace-jones-danny-brown-mavis-staples-more/|title=Gorillaz Announce New Album Humanz Featuring Grace Jones, Danny Brown, Mavis Staples, More|website=Pitchfork|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref> Their sixth studio album, ''[[The Now Now]]'', was released on 29 June 2018.\nGorillaz are currently working on a project named ''[[Song Machine]]'' which releases new songs every month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gorillaz.lnk.to/TNN?ref=https://www.youtube.com/|title=The Now Now by Gorillaz|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGorillaz [[List of awards and nominations received by Gorillaz|have won]] one [[Grammy Award]], two [[MTV Video Music Awards]], an [[NME Award]] and three [[MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref>[http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-g/gorillaz.htm Rock On The Net: Gorillaz] Rock on the Net</ref> They have been nominated for ten [[Brit Award]]s and won [[Brit Award for British Group|Best British Group]] at the [[2018 Brit Awards]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-42677246 \"Brit Awards 2018: The winners and nominees\"]. BBC. Retrieved 21 February 2018</ref><ref name=\"Brit Awards\">[http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/gorillaz Gorillaz BRITS Profile]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202033222/http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/gorillaz|date=2 February 2012}} BRIT Awards Ltd</ref> By 2010, Gorillaz had sold over 20 million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|first=Jim|last=Harrington|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2010/10/30/review-gorillaz-not-monkeying-around-with-virtual-band-anymore/|title=Review: Gorillaz not monkeying around with virtual band anymore/|newspaper=[[The Mercury News]]|date=30 October 2010|access-date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Creation (1990\u20131999)===\n[[File:Damon Albarn - Gorillaz - Roskilde Festival 2010.jpg|thumb|left|[[Damon Albarn]], co-creator of Gorillaz]]\nMusician [[Damon Albarn]] and comic creator [[Jamie Hewlett]] met in 1990 when guitarist [[Graham Coxon]], a fan of Hewlett's work, asked him to interview [[Blur (band)|Blur]], a band Albarn and Coxon had recently formed.<ref name=\"Elliot\">{{cite journal|last=Elliot|first=Paul|date=August 2001|title=FEATURE: Damon and Jamie Interview. HEY HEY WE\u2019RE THE MONKEYS!|url=http://gorillaz-news.livejournal.com/11140.html|journal=[[Q magazine|Q]]|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> The interview was published in [[Deadline (magazine)|''Deadline'']] magazine, home of Hewlett's [[comic strip]] ''[[Tank Girl]]''. Hewlett initially thought Albarn was \"arsey, a wanker\"; despite becoming acquaintances with the band, they often did not get on, especially after Hewlett began seeing Coxon's ex-girlfriend Jane Olliver.<ref name=Elliot /> Despite this, Albarn and Hewlett started sharing a flat on [[Westbourne Grove]] in London in 1997.<ref>{{cite journal |first = Chris |last = Heath |authorlink = Chris Heath |date=November 2007 |url=http://www.vblurpage.com/articles/stories/q_07.htm |title = The 21 People Who Changed Music: Damon Albarn |journal = [[Q (magazine)|Q]] |page = 87 |accessdate =24 April 2017}}</ref> Hewlett had recently broken up with Olliver and Albarn was at the end of his highly publicised relationship with [[Justine Frischmann]] of [[Elastica]].<ref name=Elliot />\n\nThe idea to create Gorillaz came about when Albarn and Hewlett were watching [[MTV]]. Hewlett said, \"If you watch MTV for too long, it's a bit like hell&nbsp;\u2013 there's nothing of substance there. So we got this idea for a virtual band, something that would be a comment on that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.07/gorillaz.html |title=Keeping It (Un)real|accessdate=5 October 2008|first=Neil|last=Gaiman|authorlink=Neil Gaiman|date=July 2005|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105225835/http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.07/gorillaz.html|archivedate=5 January 2010|url-status=live}}<!-- Page 2 archive URL: https://www.webcitation.org/5mqkDI6O2?url=http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.07/gorillaz.html?pg%3D2%26topic%3Dgorillaz%26topic_set%3D --></ref> The band originally identified themselves as \"Gorilla\" and the first song they recorded was \"Ghost Train\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1503836/060905/gorillaz.jhtml|title=Gorillaz: Who Can It Be Now?|accessdate=10 October 2007|first=Jim|last=Macnie|date=9 June 2005|publisher=[[VH1]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506223813/http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1503836/060905/gorillaz.jhtml|archivedate=6 May 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> which was later released as a [[B-side]] on their single \"[[Rock the House (Gorillaz song)|Rock the House]]\" and the B-side compilation ''[[G Sides]]''. The musicians behind Gorillaz' first incarnation included Albarn, [[Del the Funky Homosapien]], [[Dan the Automator]] and [[Kid Koala]], who had previously worked together on the track \"Time Keeps on Slipping\" for [[Deltron 3030]]'s [[Deltron 3030 (album)|eponymous debut album]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r480919|pure_url=yes}}|title=Deltron 3030 review|accessdate=27 March 2007|first=Steve|last=Huey|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\nAlthough not released under the Gorillaz name, Albarn has said that \"one of the first ever Gorillaz tunes\" was [[Blur (band)|Blur]]'s 1997 single \"[[On Your Own (Blur song)|On Your Own]]\", which was released for their fifth studio album ''[[Blur (Blur album)|Blur]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/media/s2854145.htm|last1=McDougall|first1=Lindsay|title=Gorillaz's Damon Albarn interview (part 2)|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Gorillaz'' (2000\u201303) ===\n{{listen\n|filename=Gorillaz - Clint Eastwood (sample).ogg\n|title=\"Clint Eastwood\"\n|description=\"[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\" exemplifies the mix of musical styles found on the band's debut album, combining hip hop, electronic and dub influences. The verses are rapped by [[Del the Funky Homosapien]] and the chorus is sung by [[Damon Albarn]].\n}}\nThe band's first release was the [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Tomorrow Comes Today]]'', released on 27 November 2000. The band's first single was \"[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\" and was released on 5 March 2001. It was produced by [[hip hop music|hip hop]] producer [[Dan the Automator]] and originally featured UK rap group [[Phi Life Cypher]], but the version that appears on the album features American rapper [[Del the Funky Homosapien]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/sep01/articles/gorillaztracks.asp|title=Recording Gorillaz's 'Clint Eastwood'|work=Sound on Sound|accessdate=20 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225224656/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/sep01/articles/gorillaztracks.asp|archivedate=25 December 2011}}</ref> known on the album as ''Del tha' Ghost Rapper'', a spirit in the band's drummer [[Russel Hobbs]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Cass|authorlink=Cass Browne|author2=Gorillaz|title=[[Rise of the Ogre]]|date=2 November 2006|publisher=Penguin|location=United States|isbn=1-59448-931-9|page=41}}</ref> The Phi Life Cypher version of \"Clint Eastwood\" appears on the B-side album ''[[G Sides]]''. On 26 March 2001, their first full-length album, the [[eponym|self-titled]] ''[[Gorillaz (album)|Gorillaz]]'', was released, producing four singles: \"[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\", \"[[19-2000]]\", \"[[Rock the House (Gorillaz song)|Rock the House]]\", and \"[[Tomorrow Comes Today]]\". In June 2001, \"19\u20132000\" a remix of the song was used as the title theme for [[EA Sports]] ''[[FIFA (video game series)|FIFA]]'' video game ''[[FIFA Football 2002]]''.<ref name=\"Singles chart\">David Roberts (2006). [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]. London: Guinness World Records Limited</ref>\n\nOn 7 December, the song \"[[911 (Gorillaz song)|911]]\" was released, a collaboration between Gorillaz and hip hop group [[D12 (band)|D12]] (without [[Eminem]]) and [[Terry Hall (singer)|Terry Hall]] about the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Cass|authorlink=Cass Browne|author2=Gorillaz|title=[[Rise of the Ogre]]|date=2 November 2006|publisher=Penguin|location=United States|isbn=1-59448-931-9|page=99}}</ref> Meanwhile, ''G Sides'', a compilation of the B-sides from the ''Tomorrow Comes Today'' EP and first three singles, was released in Japan on 12 December. Gorillaz performed at the [[2002 Brit Awards]] in London on 22 February, appearing in [[3D animation]] on four large screens along with rap accompaniment by [[Phi Life Cypher]]. The band were nominated for four [[Brit Awards]], including [[Brit Award for British Group|Best British Group]], Best British Album and [[Brit Award for British Breakthrough Act|British Breakthrough Act]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1760402.stm|title=Brit Awards 2002: The nominations|accessdate=11 February 2009|date=14 January 2002|work=BBC News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111005221/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1760402.stm|archivedate=11 November 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> but did not win any awards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/G/Gorillaz/2002/02/23/745445.html|title=Gorillaz come out of the mist|accessdate=11 February 2009|first=Kieran|last=Grant|date=23 February 2002|work=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120709161655/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/G/Gorillaz/2002/02/23/745445.html|archivedate=9 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2002, a [[remix album]] titled ''[[Laika Come Home]]'' by [[Spacemonkeyz]] vs. Gorillaz was released. It contains most of the songs from  Gorillaz' first album, ''Gorillaz'', but remixed in [[Dub music|dub]] and [[reggae]] style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/gorillaz/6476|title=NME Album Reviews \u2013 Space Monkeys vs. Gorillaz: Laika Come Home|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> On 18 November, a DVD titled ''[[Phase One: Celebrity Take Down]]'' was released. The DVD contains four promotional videos, the abandoned video for \"[[5/4 (song)|5/4]]\", the ''Charts of Darkness'' documentary, the five Gorilla Bitez (comedic shorts starring the virtual characters), a tour of the website by the MEL 9000 server and more. The DVD's menu was designed much like the band's website and depicts an abandoned Kong Studios.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/18165-phase-one-celebrity-take-down-dvd|title=Phase One: Celebrity Take Down DVD|accessdate=11 February 2009|first=Rob|last=Mitchum|date=5 February 2003|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104010306/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/3525-phase-one-celebrity-take-down-dvd/|archivedate=4 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nRumours were circulating at this time that the Gorillaz team were busy preparing a film, but Hewlett said that the film project had been abandoned: \"We lost all interest in doing it as soon as we started meeting with studios and talking to these Hollywood executive types, we just weren't on the same page. We said, fuck it, we'll sit on the idea until we can do it ourselves, and maybe even raise the money ourselves.\"<ref name=\"Big Issue\">{{cite journal|last=Joseph|first=Michael|date=2 November 2006|title=Gorillaz in the Midst|journal=[[The Big Issue]] in Scotland|issue=604|page=13}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Demon Days'' (2004\u201306) ===\nThe album ''[[Demon Days]]'' was released on 11 May 2005. The album debuted at No.&nbsp;1 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/album/13902|title=Gorillaz&nbsp;\u2013 Demon Days&nbsp;\u2013 Music Charts|accessdate=9 October 2007|work=\u03b1Charts.us}}</ref> The third single was \"[[Dirty Harry (song)|Dirty Harry]]\", which had been released as a promotional single earlier that year. It was released in the United Kingdom on 21 November. The fourth and final single was a [[double A-side]], \"[[Kids with Guns]]\" / \"[[El Ma\u00f1ana (song)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]\". It was released in the UK on 10 April 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/discog/elmanana.php |title=El Ma\u00f1ana / Kids With Guns |accessdate=7 March 2007 |year=2006 |work=fans.gorillaz.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107173510/http://fans.gorillaz.com/discog/elmanana.php |archivedate=7 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In December 2005, ''Demon Days'' had sold over a million copies in the UK, making it the UK's fifth best selling album of 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.bpi.co.uk/news/printerFriendly/print.asp?nwz_id=news_content_file_966.shtml |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160411081626/http://www.bpi.co.uk/news/printerFriendly/print.asp?nwz_id=news_content_file_966.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-date = 11 April 2016 |title = UK record industry releases 2005 sales figures |accessdate =7 December 2008 |date = 6 January 2006 |publisher = [[British Phonographic Industry]] }}</ref> ''Demon Days'' has since gone six times platinum in the UK,<ref name=\"Platinum UK\"/> double platinum in the United States,<ref name=\"Platinum US\"/> triple platinum in Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/ARIACharts-Accreditations-2006Albums.htm |title=ARIA Charts&nbsp;\u2013 Accreditations&nbsp;\u2013 2006 Albums |accessdate=3 April 2007 |year=2006 |publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102034739/http://www.aria.com.au/pages/ARIACharts-Accreditations-2006Albums.htm |archivedate=2 January 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and has sold over 8&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emimusicpub.com/worldwide/artist_profile/gorillaz_profile.html |title=Artist Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gorillaz |accessdate=7 December 2008 |year=2006 |publisher=[[EMI]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081115114738/http://www.emimusicpub.com/worldwide/artist_profile/gorillaz_profile.html |archivedate=15 November 2008 }}</ref> At the [[2005 MTV Video Music Awards]] in Miami on 28 August, Gorillaz won two awards for \"[[Feel Good Inc.]]\" featuring [[De La Soul]], including the award for [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video|Breakthrough Video]].<ref>[http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2005/mtvvmas.htm 2005 MTV Video Music Awards] Rock on the Net. Retrieved 7 December 2011</ref>\n\n[[File:De La Soul Demon Days Live.jpg|thumb|left|[[De La Soul]] performing \"Feel Good Inc.\" with Gorillaz at the [[Demon Days Live]] concert in Manchester, England]]\nGorillaz performed \"Dirty Harry\" at the [[2006 Brit Awards]] in London, and the band were nominated for [[Brit Award for British Group|Best British Group]], and Best British Album (''Demon Days'').<ref name=\"Brit Awards\"/> Plans were unveiled for Gorillaz to go on a \"holographic\" world tour in 2007 and 2008.<ref name=\"worldtour\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/sep/08/gorillaz.popandrock |title=Gorillaz to tour&nbsp;\u2013 in 3D |accessdate=11 October 2008 |first=Dave |last=Simpson |date=8 September 2008 |work=The Guardian |location=UK |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015122232/http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2005/sep/08/gorillaz.popandrock |archivedate=15 October 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref> The virtual members would be shown as virtual characters on stage using [[Musion Eyeliner]] technology, giving them a lifelike appearance on stage. The virtual characters were first used at the [[2005 MTV Europe Music Awards]] on 3 November,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_case_study.html |title=Gorillaz at the MTV Awards 2005 |accessdate=9 September 2007 |year=2006 |publisher=Dimensional Studios |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329154828/http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_case_study.html |archivedate=29 March 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref> and again at the [[48th Grammy Awards|2006 Grammy Awards]], on 8 February 2006 with the addition of [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], where the band played a pre-recorded version of \"Feel Good Inc.\"<ref name=\"Grammy Madonna\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_madonna_grammy_awards.html |title=Gorillaz & Madonna&nbsp;\u2013 Grammy Awards 2006 |accessdate=5 November 2006 |year=2006 |publisher=Dimensional Studios |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304115414/http://www.eyeliner3d.com/gorillaz_madonna_grammy_awards.html |archivedate=4 March 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:GorillazKidrobot.jpg|thumb|right|All the Kidrobot figures that were released. The black set, red set, special \"[[Dare (song)|Dare]]\" [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]], four-color set, white set and two-tone set]]\nDuring 16 October\u20132 November, a set of Gorillaz figures were released by [[Kidrobot]] to coincide with the release of ''[[Demon Days]]''. Two variations of the set were released, known as the Red and Black editions, and a limited edition [[Noodle (character)|Noodle]] from the music video for \"[[Dare (song)|Dare]]\" was also released.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/62712/gorillaz-going-out-on-virtual-us-tour \"Gorillaz going out on virtual U.S. tour\"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 30 July 2015</ref> Three new sets of Gorillaz vinyl figures were released in 2006. The basic set which was limited to 60,000 was the two-tone set limited to 1,000 and the white edition which was limited to 4,000 were released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.virginrecords.com/home/news.aspx?&action=search&Keyword=Gorillaz%20Phase%20Two&submitButton=Search |title=Gorillaz Phase Two&nbsp;\u2013 Slowboat to Hades DVD Released 31&nbsp;October |accessdate=7 December 2008 |date=9 October 2006 |publisher=[[Virgin Records]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130205152618/http://www.virginrecords.com/home/news.aspx?&action=search&Keyword=Gorillaz+Phase+Two&submitButton=Search|archivedate=5 February 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> On 26 October, the Gorillaz [[autobiography]] titled ''[[Rise of the Ogre]]'' by [[Riverhead Books]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9781594489310,00.html|title=Rise of the Ogre (US)|accessdate=2007-08-27|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200126/http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0%2C%2C9781594489310%2C00.html|archivedate=2007-09-30|df=}}</ref> was released on UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penguin.co.uk/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780718150006,00.html|title=Rise of the Ogre (UK)|accessdate=2007-08-27|date=26 October 2006|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915173058/http://www.penguin.co.uk/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780718150006,00.html|archivedate=2007-09-15|df=}}</ref> 2 November 2006 on US. On 30 October, the ''[[Phase Two: Slowboat to Hades]]'' DVD was released on UK. 25 October in Japan. 31 October in the US. And 11 November in Australia. It contains the most of the materials released by Gorillaz from 2004 to 2006. The MTV EMAs, Grammys and Brits live performances. Also included is the Gorillaz' ''[[MTV Cribs]]'' episode, the Phase Two Gorillaz bites, a new Kong Studios guide, a gallery, and short interviews.\n\nOn 2 June 2006 the hopes for a Gorillaz film were revived, when Hewlett stated that they would be producing the film on their own. Film producer and [[The Weinstein Company]] co-chairman, [[Harvey Weinstein]], was said to be in talks with Albarn and Hewlett.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20060602013348612 |title=Gorillaz: The Movie |accessdate=1 October 2006 |first=Peter |last=Sciretta |date=2 June 2006 |work=[[/Film]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404133619/http://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20060602013348612 |archivedate=4 April 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In a September 2006 interview with [[Uncut (magazine)|''Uncut'']] magazine, Albarn was said that the band \"has been a fantastic journey which isn't over, because we're making a film. We've got [[Terry Gilliam]] involved. But as far as being in a big band and putting pop music out there, it's finished. We won't be doing that any more.\"<ref name=\"Uncut\">{{cite journal |last = Williamson |first = Nigel |date=November 2006 |title = West London Calling |journal = [[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |page = 88}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2007, a [[compilation album]] titled ''[[D-Sides]]'' was released. It contains [[A-side and B-side|B-sides]] and [[remix]]es from [[single (music)|singles]] and [[bonus tracks]] for the band's second [[studio album]] ''[[Demon Days]]'', as well as previously unreleased tracks recorded during the same sessions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#070918|title=D-Sides Confirmed|accessdate=19 September 2007|date=18 September 2007|work=fans.gorillaz.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324065333/http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#070918|archivedate=24 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#071020|title=D-Sides Deluxe Preview|accessdate=3 November 2007|date=20 October 2007|work=fans.gorillaz.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324065333/http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0719.php#071020|archivedate=24 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Only one video out in 8 December 2004, \"[[Rockit (Gorillaz song)|Rockit]] (or \"Rock It\").<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first=Cass|authorlink=Cass Browne|author2=Gorillaz|title=[[Rise of the Ogre]]|date=2 November 2006|publisher=Penguin|location=United States|isbn=1-59448-931-9|page=204}}</ref> On 20 April 2009, a [[documentary]] titled ''[[Bananaz]]'', was released on [[PAL]] / [[Region 0]] DVD format. It contains the [[documentary film]], directed by Ceri Levy, documents the previous seven years of the band.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bananaz: Dir. Ceri Levy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/15/damon-albarn-gorillaz|accessdate=30 September 2018|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=19 April 2009}}</ref> The film was released online on the [[Babelgum]] website on 20 April 2009 followed by the DVD release on 1 June 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorillaz go Bananaz online |url=http://news.qthemusic.com/2009/04/gorillaz_movie_set_for_online.html|work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|date=9 April 2009|accessdate=17 January 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715134518/http://news.qthemusic.com/2009/04/gorillaz_movie_set_for_online.html|archivedate=15 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Plastic Beach'' and ''The Fall'' (2007\u201313) ===\n{{Listen|filename=Gorillaz - Stylo (Sample).ogg|title=\"Stylo\"|description=Featuring [[Mos Def]] and [[Bobby Womack]], \"[[Stylo (song)|Stylo]]\" contained [[Electronic music|electronic]] influences.}}\nIn late 2007, Albarn and Hewlett began working on ''Carousel'', a new Gorillaz project which eventually evolved into the band's third studio album ''[[Plastic Beach]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last = Lynskey |first = Dorian |date=December 2007 |title = Damon Albarn |journal = [[Q (magazine)|Q]]}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian 2009\">{{cite news|last=Morley|first=Paul|url=http://audio.theguardian.tv/audio/kip/music/series/paul-morley-showing-off/1259329339795/8827/AlbarnMorleyFINAL.mp3|title=Paul Morley's Showing Off... Damon Albarn|date=27 November 2009|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=29 November 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5le8WXHB0?url=http://audio.theguardian.tv/audio/kip/music/series/paul-morley-showing-off/1259329339795/8827/AlbarnMorleyFINAL.mp3|archivedate=29 November 2009|format=MP3|authorlink=Paul Morley}}<!-- Article URL: http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2009/nov/28/showing-off-damon-albarn --></ref>\n\nAlbarn said \"I'm making this the biggest and most pop record I've ever made in many ways, but with all my experience to try and at least present something that has got depth.\"<ref name=\"guardian 2009\" /> The album features guest performances by [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Lou Reed]], [[Mos Def]], [[Bobby Womack]], [[Gruff Rhys]], [[Mark E. Smith]], [[Mick Jones (The Clash)|Mick Jones]], [[Paul Simonon]], [[Kano (rapper)|Kano]], [[Bashy]], [[De La Soul]], [[Little Dragon]], [[Hypnotic Brass Ensemble]], [[sinfonia ViVA]], and the Lebanese National Orchestra for Oriental Arabic Music.<ref name=\"guardian 2009\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/05/de-la-nike.html |title=De La Soul's Posdnuos on their Nike mix, their next album, and working again with Gorillaz |accessdate=29 May 2009 |first=Simon |last=Vozick-Levinson |date=28 May 2009 |work=Entertainment Weekly |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815140629/http://music-mix.ew.com/2009/05/28/de-la-nike/ |archivedate=15 August 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=Pitchfork>{{cite news|title=Gorillaz Reveal Full Album Details |first=Amy |last=Phillips |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/37638-gorillaz-reveal-full-album-details/ |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=20 January 2010 |accessdate=21 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123125020/http://pitchfork.com/news/37638-gorillaz-reveal-full-album-details/ |archivedate=23 January 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2010, it was announced that Gorillaz would be headlining the final night of the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] on 18 April 2010.<ref name=\"coachella\">{{cite news|title=2010 Coachella Line Up is here |url=http://coachella.com/updates/news/2010lineup |publisher=[[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] |date=18 January 2010 |accessdate=20 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123000304/http://coachella.com/updates/news/2010lineup |archivedate=23 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\nThe first single from the album, \"[[Stylo (song)|Stylo]]\", featuring Bobby Womack and Mos Def was made available for download 26 January 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Gorillaz Song 'Stylo' Hits The Web |first=James |last=Montgomery |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1630062/20100120/gorillaz.jhtml |work=[[MTV News]] |date=20 January 2010 |accessdate=21 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123020030/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1630062/20100120/gorillaz.jhtml |archivedate=23 January 2010 |url-status=live  }}</ref> In October 2010, Albarn announced to the media that he would not let the cast of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' cover the band's songs, claiming that the music on the Fox network's TV show is a \"very poor substitute for the real thing\". This statement led most people to believe that Gorillaz had been asked by ''Glee'' producers to lend their music to the show, which they had not. Albarn responded to the confusion with a laugh and said \"and now they definitely won't.\"<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/954190/gorillaz-we-wont-let-glee-cover-our-songs |title = Gorillaz: We Won't Let 'Glee' Cover Our Songs |work = Billboard |date = 14 September 2009 |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 October 2010, Gorillaz announced their new single \"[[Doncamatic]]\" featuring [[Daley (musician)|Daley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gorillaz.com/news/news/breaking-news-brand-new-gorillaz-single-to-be-played-on-zane-lowe-show-youtube-tonight |title=News \u2013 BREAKING NEWS! Brand new Gorillaz single to be played on Zane Lowe show & Youtube tonight! |publisher=Gorillaz.com |date=5 October 2010 |accessdate=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711113046/http://gorillaz.com/news/news/breaking-news-brand-new-gorillaz-single-to-be-played-on-zane-lowe-show-youtube-tonight |archivedate=11 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> On 8 December 2010, Albarn confirmed that a Gorillaz album recorded on the American leg of the Escape to Plastic Beach tour would be released to download for free exclusively to paying fan club members from the Gorillaz website on Christmas Day, 25 December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/entertainment/a/-/entertainment/8473116/gorillaz-in-the-hits/ |title = Gorillaz in the hits \u2013 The West Australian |work = Yahoo! News |date = 8 December 2010 |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref> The video for \"[[Phoner to Arizona]]\" was released on Gorillaz' website for free on 24 December and, a day later, their new album was released, entitled ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://pitchfork.com/news/41023-gorillaz-name-ipad-album/ |title = Gorillaz Name iPad Album |work = Pitchfork |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2011, Gorillaz announced the release of their own version of the iPad app iElectribe, by [[Korg]] \u2013 which features loops and samples taken from ''The Fall'' as well as other samples. The new version features a Gorillaz designed and styled interface; it is customised to generate Gorillaz samples from their album ''The Fall'' and includes 128 new sounds created by the band and 64 ready-to-use pre-programmed patterns from Gorillaz, Stephen Sedgwick (Gorillaz' engineer) and [[Korg]]. The app was based on Korg's Electribe: R device app.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.gorillaz-unofficial.com/news/index.htm |title = GorillazUnofficial 100% unofficial. 100% Gorillaz |publisher = Gorillaz-unofficial.com |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = https://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/korg-ielectribe-gorillaz-edition/id430288460?mt%3D8 |title = KORG iELECTRIBE Gorillaz Edition for iPad on the iTunes App Store |publisher = iTunes Store |date = 26 May 2011 |accessdate =18 July 2011 }}</ref> On 5 October 2011, Gorillaz released their first \"greatest hits\" compilation, ''[[The Singles Collection 2001\u20132011]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gorillaz.com/news/news/10-years-of-gorillaz-the-singles-collection |title=News \u2013 10 Years of Gorillaz! |date=5 October 2011 |accessdate=15 October 2011 |publisher=Gorillaz |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007235018/http://gorillaz.com/news/news/10-years-of-gorillaz-the-singles-collection |archivedate=7 October 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 February 2012, Gorillaz announced \"[[DoYaThing]]\", a single to promote the Gorillaz-branded [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]] shoes that were soon to be released. The song would be part of Converse's \"Three Artists, One Song\" projects, with the two collaborators being [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] of [[LCD Soundsystem]] and [[Andr\u00e9 3000]] of [[Outkast]]. An explicit, 13-minute-long version of the song became available for listening shortly after on Gorillaz.com. Hewlett returned to direct the single's music video, featuring animated versions of the two collaborators on the track.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gorillaz-unofficial.com/news/ |title=GorillazUnofficial 100% unofficial. 100% Gorillaz |publisher=Gorillaz-unofficial.com |accessdate=31 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326063451/http://gorillaz-unofficial.com/news/ |archivedate=26 March 2012  }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, Albarn told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he and Hewlett had fallen out and that future Gorillaz projects were \"unlikely\".<ref name=\"harris1\">{{cite news |title=Damon Albarn: Gorillaz, heroin and the last days of Blur |author=Harris, John |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/apr/07/damon-albarn-gorillaz-heroin-blur? |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group plc|Guardian News and Media]] |location=London/Manchester |date=7 April 2012 |page=1 |accessdate=7 April 2012 }}</ref> Tension between the two had been building, partly due to a belief held by Hewlett that his contributions to Gorillaz were being diminished. Speaking to ''The Guardian'' in April 2017, Hewlett explained: \"Damon had half the Clash on stage, and Bobby Womack and Mos Def and De La Soul, and fucking Hypnotic Brass Ensemble and Bashy and everyone else. It was the greatest band ever. And the screen on stage behind them seemed to get smaller every day. I\u2019d say, \u2018Have we got a new screen?\u2019 and the tour manager was like, \u2018No, it\u2019s the same screen.\u2019 Because it seemed to me like it was getting smaller.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Damon Albarn and Jamie Hewlett: \u2018We fight over everything\u2019 |author=Sawyer, Miranda |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/apr/30/damon-albarn-and-jamie-hewlett-we-fight-over-everything-gorillaz-humanz-interview |work=The Guardian |date=30 April 2017 |accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref> On 25 April 2012, in an interview with Metro, Albarn was more optimistic about Gorillaz' future, saying that once he had worked out his differences with Hewlett, he was sure that they would make another record.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams |first=Andrew |url=http://www.metro.co.uk/music/897126-damon-albarn-blur-and-gorillaz-arent-finished-yet |title=Damon Albarn: Blur and Gorillaz aren't finished yet &#124; Metro News |work=Metro|location=UK |date=24 April 2012 |accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> On 24 June 2013, Hewlett stated that he and Albarn planned to someday record a follow-up to their 2010 album ''[[Plastic Beach]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Guardian music |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jun/24/blur-gorillaz-new-albums-damon-albarn |title=Blur and Gorillaz will both make new albums, says Albarn collaborator  |work=The Guardian |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/51295-blur-and-gorillaz-will-release-new-albums-gorillaz-jamie-hewlett-says/ |title=Blur and Gorillaz Will Release New Albums, Gorillaz' Jamie Hewlett Says  |work=Pitchfork |date=24 June 2013 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Humanz'' (2014\u201317) ===\nIn April 2014, Albarn told the ''[[National Post]]'' that he \"wouldn't mind having another stab at a Gorillaz record.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = http://arts.nationalpost.com/2014/04/29/i-dont-take-britpop-seriously-and-no-one-should-damon-albarn-does-a-rare-bit-of-looking-back-on-his-first-solo-record/ |archive-url = https://archive.today/20140501210752/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2014/04/29/i-dont-take-britpop-seriously-and-no-one-should-damon-albarn-does-a-rare-bit-of-looking-back-on-his-first-solo-record/ |url-status=dead |archive-date = 1 May 2014 |title = 'I don't take Britpop seriously and no one should': Damon Albarn does a rare bit of looking back on his first solo record, Everyday Robots |first = Jonathan |last = Dekel |date = 29 April 2014 |work = National Post }}</ref> Two months later he reported that he had \"been writing quite a lot of songs on the road for Gorillaz\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2014/06/bonnaroo-2014-damon-albarn-interview|title=Damon Albarn Hypes Up New Gorillaz Tracks|publisher=Fuse|date=15 June 2014|accessdate=19 October 2014|author=Xu, Tina|page=1}}</ref> On 19 October 2014, Albarn told ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' that he was planning to release new Gorillaz material in 2016.<ref name=\"Kaye, Ben 1\">{{cite magazine | url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/10/damon-albarn-new-gorillaz-album-coming-in-2016/ | title=Damon Albarn says new Gorillaz album coming in 2016 | magazine=Consequence of Sound | date=19 October 2014 | accessdate=19 October 2014 | author=Kaye, Ben | page=1}}</ref> Albarn has described the music that he has written for the next Gorillaz album as being very upbeat, humorous, and positive, stating that he plans on giving the tracks \"a benchmark of 125 bpm and nothing underneath that\", while also suggesting that it once again may have many collaborations.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Ben|title=Swide|url=http://www.swide.com/art-culture/damon-albarn-music-interview-about-everyday-robots-album-2014-blur-and-tour/2014/06/17|website=Swide.com|accessdate=25 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610173916/http://www.swide.com/art-culture/damon-albarn-music-interview-about-everyday-robots-album-2014-blur-and-tour/2014/06/17|archive-date=10 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lindsay|first1=Cam|title=Damon Albarn in the Spotlight|url=http://exclaim.ca/Music/article/damon_albarn-in_spotlight|work=Exclaim!|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Book|first1=Ryan|title=Damon Albarn Writing A Musical While Flirting with Blur and Gorillaz Comebacks|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/7797/20140721/damon-albarn-writing-musical-flirting-blur-gorillaz-comebacks.htm|work=The Music Times|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> On 16 July 2015, Albarn stated during an interview for ABC's [[7.30]] in Australia that he would begin work on the next Gorillaz album: \"I'm starting recording in September for a new Gorillaz record, I've just been really, really busy so I haven't had a chance. I'd love to just get back in to that routine of being at home and coming to the studio five days a week.\"<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6634331/gorillaz-new-album-2015-damon-albarn \"Damon Albarn: New Gorillaz Album Coming, Recording Starts in September\"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 31 July 2015</ref>\n\nSpeaking about his relationship with Hewlett, Albarn said that the pair's well-publicized fall-out has helped their relationship in the long term.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/gorillaz/88966 |title=New Gorillaz album will be released in 2016, says Jamie Hewlett |work=NME |date=12 October 2015 |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> In October 2015, Albarn revealed to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' that he and Hewlett were working on a new Gorillaz album.<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/damon-albarn-on-blurs-big-return-banksy-really-fast-new-gorillaz-lp-20151014?page=2 \"Damon Albarn on Blur's Big Return, Banksy, 'Really Fast' New Gorillaz LP\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915113916/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/damon-albarn-on-blurs-big-return-banksy-really-fast-new-gorillaz-lp-20151014?page=2 |date=15 September 2017 }}. Rolling Stone. Retrieved 25 October 2015</ref> In April 2016, Hewlett uploaded two video clips onto his [[Instagram]] showing the continued work on the album. The first clip featured [[Liam Bailey]] and rumoured executive producer on the album ''The Twilite Tone''. The second clip was a time-lapse video featuring Albarn, Bailey, [[The Twilite Tone]] and [[Jean-Michel Jarre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebanginbeats.com/2016/04/14/virtual-band-gorillaz-teases-their-upcoming-album-with-glimpses-inside-the-studio/ |title=Virtual Band Gorillaz Teases Their Upcoming Album with Glimpses Inside The Studio |first=Surbhi |last=Mittal |date=14 April 2016 |work=thebanginbeats.com |accessdate=23 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625081736/http://thebanginbeats.com/2016/04/14/virtual-band-gorillaz-teases-their-upcoming-album-with-glimpses-inside-the-studio/ |archivedate=25 June 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/gorillaz-phase-4-first-footage-of-jamie-hewlett-and-damon-albarn-in-studio-emerges-online-a6980866.html|title=First footage of Damon Albarn working on new Gorillaz album emerges online|date=12 April 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7326580/gorillaz-jamie-hewlett-studio-videos-new-album-sessions-albarn|title=Gorillaz's Jamie Hewlett Posts In-Studio Videos of New Album Sessions|work=Billboard|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref> On 17 May 2016, Gorillaz were in the studio with Chicago-based hip hop artist [[Vic Mensa]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brennan|first1=Collin|title=Gorillaz hit the studio with Chicago rapper Vic Mensa|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/05/gorillaz-hit-the-studio-with-chicago-rapper-vic-mensa/|website=Consequenceofsound.net|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/gorillaz/93634|title=Vic Mensa pictured in the studio with Gorillaz|work=NME|last1=Renshaw|first1=David|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mitchell|first1=Chris|title=Vic Mensa spotted in studio with Gorillaz|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.38856/title.vic-mensa-spotted-in-studio-with-gorillaz|website=HipHopDX.com|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=El|title=It was Mensa be: GORILLAZ ARE WORKING WITH VIC MENSA ON THEIR NEW ALBUM|url=https://diymag.com/2016/05/18/gorillaz-recording-with-vic-mensa|website=DIYMag.com|accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2016, Gorillaz began an abridged retrospective timeline of the history of Gorillaz releases since 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Monroe|first1=Jazz|title=Gorillaz Launch Instagram Account, Career-Spanning Timeline|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/68410-gorillaz-are-now-on-instagram/|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Harrison|title=GORILLAZ LAUNCH A NEW INSTAGRAM ACCOUNT AND WEBSITE ALLUDING TO THEIR ALBUM|url=http://mixmag.net/read/gorillaz-launch-new-instagram-account-and-website-new-album-coming-soon-news|work=Mixmag|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bein|first1=Kat|title=Gorillaz Launch New Instagram, Website Ahead of Forthcoming Album|url=https://billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7517934/gorillaz-new-instagram-website-2017-album?|work=Billboard|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> On 3 October 2016, Gorillaz began posting a series of interactive multimedia stories revolving around the fictional lives of each Gorillaz character since their hiatus to their social media profiles, beginning with ''The Book of Noodle'' (she ended up in Japan and tracked down a demon crime boss), then ''The Book of Russel'' (he was still a giant from the storyline of Plastic Beach, where he washed up on the shores of North Korea and starved so much he shrank back to normal size), then ''The Book of Murdoc'' (he was captured by the band's record label [[EMI]] at sea and told to make another album), and finishing with ''The Book of 2-D'' (he was swallowed by a whale named Massive Dick on Plastic Beach, and washed up on the shores of Mexico where, to survive, he had to eat the whale's blubber, but it turned out he was just at an empty part of [[Cabo San Lucas]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Alex|title=Gorillaz kick off phase four with The Book of Noodle|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/10/gorillaz-kick-off-phase-four-with-the-book-of-noodle/|website=ConsequenceofSound.net|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Gorillaz, Brixton Academy, London (34377484273).jpg|thumb|left|Gorillaz (with Albarn to the left) on stage at the [[Brixton Academy]] in London, June 2017]]\nOn 8 October 2016, Noodle was given her own [[Instagram]] page and was announced to be the Global Ambassador of [[Jaguar Racing]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morgan Britton|first1=Luke|title=Watch Gorillaz team up with Jaguar Racing for new short film starring Noodle. |url=https://www.nme.com/news/gorillaz/96954|work=NME|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> On 19 January 2017, a new song from the band entitled \"[[Hallelujah Money]]\" featuring [[Benjamin Clementine]] was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/music/gorillaz-hallelujah-money-video/2/|title=Gorillaz Return After Six Years With Political, Apocalyptic New Video|date=19 January 2017|publisher=uproxx.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/gorillaz-return-their-first-new-song-6-years-halle-248692|title=Gorillaz return with their first new song in 6 years, \"Hallelujah Money\"|date=19 January 2017|access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref> On 6 March, Gorillaz announced the launch of their own festival, called Demon Dayz Festival, which took place on 10 June 2017 at [[Dreamland Margate]] in [[Margate]], Kent, England.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trendell|first1=Andrew|title=Gorillaz announce huge UK comeback show with their own festival at Dreamland, Margate |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/gorillaz-announce-huge-uk-comeback-show-dreamland-margate-2003709|work=NME|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Renshaw|first1=David|title=Gorillaz Has Announced Its Live Return As Part of Their Own Festival|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/03/06/gorillaz-demon-dayz-festival|website=thefader.com|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Alex|title=Gorillaz announce first live performance in five years with launch of their own Demon Dayz festival|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/gorillaz-announce-first-live-performance-in-five-years-with-launch-of-their-own-demon-dayz-festival/|website=Consequenceofsound.net|publisher=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> The band headlined the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indieshuffle.com/news/gorillaz-first-show-since-2010-headlining-demon-dayz-festival/|title=Gorillaz Announce First Show Since 2010 :: Indie Shuffle|website=indieshuffle.com|access-date=7 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2017, the tracklist of the forthcoming album was leaked online, showing guest features from a variety of artists including usual collaborators De La Soul, as well as new collaborators such as [[Grace Jones]], [[Vince Staples]], [[Pusha T]], [[Rag'n'Bone Man]], [[Anthony Hamilton (musician)|Anthony Hamilton]], [[Kilo Kish]] and [[Kali Uchis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tracklist for new Gorillaz album reportedly leaks|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/new-gorillaz-album-tracklist-leaks-2020874|last1=Thomas|first1=Helen|work=[[NME]]|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Vince Staples, Danny Brown and more to feature on new Gorillaz album according to leaked tracklist|url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/03/18/vince-staples-danny-brown-feature-new-gorillaz-album-according-leaked-tracklist/|last=Bychawski|first=Adam|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Grace Jones, Kelela, Danny Brown Rumored to Appear on New Gorillaz Album|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/gorillaz-new-album-rumors|last=Julious|first=Britt|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=18 March 2017|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2017, Gorillaz announced via Instagram that the new album will be entitled ''[[Humanz]]'', with a scheduled release date of 28 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1931383/four-new-gorillaz-songs-appear-on-tidal/news/ |title=New Gorillaz Album Humanz Out 4/28 |publisher=[[Stereogum]] |date=23 March 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> On the official Gorillaz YouTube page, two new music videos were released for their track \"[[Saturnz Barz]]\", one of which was in a 360\u00ba view. The track features vocals from Jamaican dancehall artist [[Popcaan]]. The band also released an art video for the track \"[[Andromeda (song)|Andromeda]]\", featuring an animated planet in a galaxy. The track features the American rapper [[DRAM (rapper)|D.R.A.M.]], two more art videos were released: \"[[Ascension (Gorillaz song)|Ascension]]\" (featuring American rapper Vince Staples) and \"[[We Got the Power (Gorillaz song)|We Got the Power]]\" (featuring [[Jehnny Beth]] of the English rock band [[Savages (band)|Savages]] and [[Noel Gallagher]] of [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Damon Albarn talks working with Noel Gallagher on new Gorillaz track 'We Got The Power'|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/damon-albarn-noel-gallagher-gorillaz-we-got-the-power-2026536|work=NME|date=6 April 2017}}</ref> On 6 April 2017, the fifth single from ''Humanz'', \"[[Let Me Out (Gorillaz song)|Let Me Out]]\" (featuring [[Mavis Staples]] and [[Pusha T]]), was released, followed by a performance of the song on ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' on 27 April.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cantor|first1=Brian|title=Gorillaz Perform 'Let Me Out' on Stephen Colbert's \"Late Show\"|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2017/04/27/first-look-gorillaz-perform-thursdays-late-show-stephen-colbert/|website=TV News|accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref> On 10 April 2017, a Gorillaz themed [[augmented reality]] app created in collaboration with [[Electronic Beats]] was released. On 24 April 2017, four days before the ''Humanz'' release date, another promotional single was uploaded, titled \"The Apprentice\". It is the only new song taken from the deluxe edition of ''Humanz''.\n\nOn 28 April 2017, ''Humanz'' was released worldwide. On 8 June 2017, the non-album single \"[[Sleeping Powder]]\" was released, along with an accompanying music video. On 10 June 2017, the band headlined the Demon Dayz Festival in [[Margate]], [[England]]. On 4 August 2017 the band released \"[[Strobelite]]\" as a single with an accompanying music video.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-the-video-for-gorillaz-single-strobelight-2121940 |title = Watch the video for new Gorillaz single \u2018Strobelight\u2019 |date = 7 August 2017 |agency = [[NME]] }}</ref> On 31 October 2017, \"Garage Palace\" was released as a single from the \"Super Deluxe\" Edition of ''Humanz'', which includes 14 additional songs and was released on 3 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-gorillaz-little-simz-slay-foes-in-garage-palace-video-w510734|title=Watch Gorillaz, Little Simz Slay Foes in 'Garage Palace' Video|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/05/gorillazs-humanz-vinyl-box-set-boasts-14-unreleased-bonus-tracks/|title=Gorillaz's Humanz vinyl box set boasts 14 unreleased bonus tracks|date=7 May 2017|publisher=consequenceofsound.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qoAxRICB9j8|title=Gorillaz \u2013 Garage Palace (Visualiser)|last=Gorillaz|date=31 October 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> In December 2017, the band released a ''Humanz''-themed, [[Fictional universe|in-universe]] magazine called G Magazine.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=935490663365468160|user=gorillaz|title=Murdoc Niccals here with an early xmas present for you lucky b*****ds.|author=Gorillaz|date=28 November 2017}}</ref> On 21 February 2018, the band received the [[Brit Award for British Group]] for their work on ''Humanz''. During their acceptance speech, a short-video of Murdoc was played, showing him being imprisoned for an unknown reason.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=966439918347014144|user=gorillaz|title=And now, a message from Murdoc Niccals|author=Gorillaz|date=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Now Now'' (2018\u201319) ===\nIn an interview with ''[[Q Magazine]]'' in September 2017, Albarn hinted at another potential Gorillaz album being in production. He mentioned enjoying the spontaneity of recording and debuting music while on tour, similarly to the band's 2010 release ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]'', but expressed desire to make it a comparatively more \"complete\" record, adding that \"If we're going to do more with Gorillaz we don't want to wait seven years because, y'know, we're getting on a bit now\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Gorillaz might drop a surprise album on us|url=http://mixmag.net/read/the-gorillaz-might-drop-a-surprise-new-album-on-us-news|website=Mixmag|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> At the end of the same month on 30 September 2017 while touring for ''[[Humanz]]'', the band debuted a new song in Seattle called \"Idaho\". Hewlett confirmed later on in December 2017 that the band planned to release a follow-up album to ''Humanz'' in 2018, citing a desire to keep the band going rather than take any prolonged breaks as the band had usually done with previous projects. Hewlett described several of the demos and new material as a \"new direction\" for the band, stating that he hopes to move the band's artwork in a similar direction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jamie Hewlett says Gorillaz will release a new album next year|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/12/jamie-hewlett-says-gorillaz-will-release-a-new-album-next-year/|website=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> During a performance in Chile on the final leg of the [[Humanz Tour]], Albarn confirmed that the new album was coming \"very soon\" and premiered a new song called \"[[Hollywood (Gorillaz song)|Hollywood]]\" featuring [[Jamie Principle]] and [[Snoop Dogg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/twitter/statuses/976522747030462464|title=Damon Albarn on Twitter|website=Twitter|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> On 26 May 2018, the album was officially announced to be titled ''[[The Now Now]]'', being co-produced by [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qobuz.com/gb-en/album/the-now-now-gorillaz/gopjozt6bd9wc|title=The Now Now {{!}} Gorillaz \u2013 Download and listen to the album|website=[[Qobuz]]|quote=Display track details|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Alex|title=Gorillaz tease new album, The Now Now, due out in June|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/05/gorillaz-tease-new-album/|accessdate=27 May 2018|website=Consequence of Sound|date=26 May 2018}}</ref> On 31 May, the music video for the single \"[[Humility (song)|Humility]]\" featuring [[George Benson]], was released alongside \"Lake Zurich\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Gorillaz Detail New Album, Announce Tour, Release Two New Songs|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/gorillaz-share-new-song-humility-listen/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=21 May 2018}}</ref> From 7 to 21 June, the band released the singles \"Sorcererz\", \"Fire Flies\", and \"Hollywood\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Gorillaz Debut New Songs Live, Share \"Sorcererz\": Listen|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-gorillaz-debut-4-new-songs-live/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=7 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to Gorillaz\u2019s New Song \"Fire Flies\"|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/listen-to-gorillazs-new-song-fire-flies/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=14 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gorillaz Link Up With Snoop Dogg on New Song \"Hollywood\": Listen|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/gorillaz-link-up-with-snoop-dogg-on-new-song-hollywood-listen/|accessdate=16 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=21 June 2018}}</ref> ''The Now Now'' was released on 29 June 2018. On 13 September, \"[[Tranz]]\" was released as a single along with a music video.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Gorillaz' New \"Tranz\" Video\"|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-gorillazs-new-tranz-video/|accessdate=14 September 2018|website=Pitchfork|date=13 September 2018}}</ref> All of the songs from the album have a visualizer except \"Humility\".\n\nIn the fictional Gorillaz storyline, the band introduced [[Ace (The Powerpuff Girls)|Ace]] from [[Cartoon Network]]'s animated series ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]'' as a temporary bassist of the band, filling in for the imprisoned Murdoc Niccals (as seen in the band's [[Brit Awards]] acceptance speech for ''Humanz'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/the-gorillaz-ace-powerpuff-girls/|title=The Gorillaz's New Band Member is a Powerpuff Girls Character|date=31 May 2018|website=Cbr.com|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> From 4 June to 26 October 2018, the band ran a bi-weekly [[Interactive fiction|text-adventure]] [[Alternate reality game|ARG]] called ''\"Free Murdoc\"'', in which the player assists Murdoc as he attempts to escape from prison.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1003672759917039616|user=MurdocGorillaz|title=SOS, I need your help! PRONTO. So, here\u2019s what I need you to do.. |author=Murdoc Niccals|date=4 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1011295575784984576|user=gorillaz|title=Pick your side. Murdoc fans this way|author=Gorillaz|date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nme.com/music-interviews/gorillaz-exclusive-murdoc-hits-back-2d-wormwood-scrubs-cell-2354976 |title = Gorillaz: Murdoc hits back at 2D in exclusive prison interview |date = 17 July 2018 |agency = [[NME]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1056108490769514497|user=gorillaz|title=WHO WANTS TO TALK TO UNCLE MURDOC, EH? YOU\u2019VE GOT 5 MORE HOURS!|author=Gorillaz|date=27 October 2018}}</ref> Murdoc was reunited with the band on 20 September, in time to join them on the final leg of [[The Now Now Tour]].<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1042749783205662721|user=gorillaz|title=Murdoc. He's back. In the nick of time|author=Gorillaz|date=20 September 2018}}</ref> On 25 October, the band announced they would be partnering with [[G-Shock]] to create a line of Gorillaz watches.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1055463449373880321|user=gorillaz|title=Gorillaz x G Shock: pre-order now at|author=Gorillaz|date=25 October 2018}}</ref> To promote the watches, the band released a monthly web-series called ''Mission M101''.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1042776403882766336|user=gorillaz|title=G-TIME is NOW! Part 1|author=Gorillaz|date=20 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1055458968494096384|user=gorillaz|title=G-TIME is NOW! Watch episode 2|author=Gorillaz|date=25 October 2018}}</ref> On 21 November 2019, the band announced a documentary covering the production of ''Humanz'' and ''The Now Now'' and their accompanying tours titled ''Gorillaz: Reject False Icons''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strauss |first1=Matthew |title=Gorillaz Announce New Movie Reject False Icons |url= https://pitchfork.com/news/gorillaz-announce-new-movie-reject-false-icons/ |publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=21 November 2019 |date=21 November 2019}}</ref> It was released on 16 December via a worldwide theatrical screening.<ref name=\"clash\">{{cite web |author1=Clash Music |title=Five Things We Learned From New Gorillaz Film Reject False Icons |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/five-things-we-learned-from-new-gorillaz-film-reject-false-icons |publisher=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]] |accessdate=16 December 2019 |date=16 December 2019}}</ref> Eight days later, an edited version of the documentary subtitled the \"Director's Cut\" was uploaded through the Gorillaz official YouTube page in three parts: ''Humanz'',<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vccKwyv4qxE|title=GORILLAZ: REJECT FALSE ICONS {{!}} Act One - Humanz (Director's Cut)|via=YouTube|publisher=Gorillaz|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> ''Humanz World Tour''<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zWlP1MeRkN8|title=GORILLAZ: REJECT FALSE ICONS {{!}} Act Two - Humanz World Tour (Director's Cut)|via=YouTube|publisher=Gorillaz|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> and ''The Now Now''.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qGKgMuYKqf4|title=GORILLAZ: REJECT FALSE ICONS {{!}} Act Three - The Now Now (Director's Cut)|via=YouTube|publisher=Gorillaz|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Song Machine'' (2020\u2013present) ===\nOn 28 January 2020, the band officially released images via social media teasing a concept entitled ''[[Song Machine]]''.  A 23-second promotional track entitled \"Song Machine Theme Tune\" was released on streaming services with an accompanying video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2071709/gorillaz-song-machine-season-one-tease/news/|title=Gorillaz Are Teasing Something Called 'Song Machine'|date=2020-01-28|website=Stereogum|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> The following day, further information was released regarding the project, revealing that new \"episodes\" would be released spontaneously throughout the year. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/gorillaz-new-music-video-series-song-machine-details-944519/|title=Gorillaz Detail New Music, Video Series 'Song Machine'|last=Blistein|first=Jon|last2=Blistein|first2=Jon|date=2020-01-29|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> Each episode featured previously unannounced guest musicians on new Gorillaz material, with the first being \"[[Momentary Bliss]]\", which was released on 31 January and features both British rapper [[Slowthai|Slowthai]] and the [[Kent]]-based punk rock duo [[Slaves (UK band)|Slaves]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nastylittleman.com/artists/gorillaz/|title=GORILLAZ {{!}} Nasty Little Man|website=www.nastylittleman.com|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\nUpon the premiere of \"Momentary Bliss\", Albarn revealed that the group had been in the studio with [[ScHoolboy Q]] and [[Sampa the Great]] among others, although he did say that these songs were likely to be saved for future series of ''Song Machine''.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/m000drwj</ref> The group also teased a possible collaboration with Australian band [[Tame Impala]] on [[Instagram]].<ref>https://www.nme.com/news/music/gorillaz-tease-tame-impala-collaboration-as-song-machine-project-continues-2603985</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, the band released the second episode of ''Song Machine'' entitled \"[[D\u00e9sol\u00e9]]\". The song features [[Mali|Malian]] singer [[Fatoumata Diawara]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blistein |first1=Jon |title=Gorillaz Team With Malian Star Fatoumata Diawara for New Song \u2018D\u00e9sol\u00e9\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/gorillaz-fatoumata-diawara-new-song-desole-song-machine-958067/ |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=27 February 2020 |date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Style ==\nWriters and critics have variously described Gorillaz as [[art pop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as art pop:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/11/gorillaz-review-dreamland|title=Gorillaz review \u2013 Albarn's Demon Dayz festival brings joyful apocalypse to the pier|last=Wright|first=Danny|work=The Guardian|date=1 June 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1930553/leaked-gorillaz-demos-support-rumored-new-album-tracklist/news/|title=Leaked Gorillaz Demos Support Rumored New Album Tracklist|last=Breihan|first=Tom|publisher=Stereogum|date=20 March 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/07622-gorillaz-the-singles-collection-2001-2011-review|title=Gorillaz |last=Calvert|first=John|magazine=The Quietus|date=23 December 2011|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/504508/gorillazjames-murphyandre-3000s-converse-track-the-story-behind-the-song|title=Gorillaz/James Murphy/Andre 3000's Converse Track: The Story Behind The Song|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|work=Billboard|date=21 February 2012|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/music-gorillaz-in-our-midst/104900124/|title=Music: Gorillaz in our midst|last=Boller|first=Jay|work=Star Tribune|date=17 August 2012|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|title=Leaked Gorillaz Demos Support Rumored New Album Tracklist|work=[[Yahoo Entertainment]]|first=Tom|last=Breihan|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/leaked-gorillaz-demos-support-rumored-085034988.html|quote=\"the return of Damon Albarn\u2019s beloved art-pop project Gorillaz\"|date=20 March 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}\n*{{cite web|title=Benjamin Clementine Biography|work=[[Allmusic]]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/benjamin-clementine-mn0003277471/biography|quote=\"Damon Albarn and Jamie Hewlett's art-pop project Gorillaz's fourth album, Humanz.\"|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[alternative rock]],<ref>The following references cite the band as alternative rock:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/gorillaz-plan-escape-to-plastic-beach-world-tour-2033956.html|title=Gorillaz plan \"Escape to Plastic Beach\" world tour|work=[[The Independent]]|first=|last=|date=|accessdate=10 November 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/gorillaz-update-us-what-russels-been-too-243889|title=Gorillaz update us on what Russel's been up to, too|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|first=William|last=Hughes|accessdate=14 May 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://vrscout.com/news/watch-gorillaz-360-music-video-vr-headset|title=How To Watch The Gorillaz 360\u00b0 Music Video on Any VR Headset \u2013 VRScout|date=28 March 2017|publisher=vrscout.com}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/new-gorillaz-music-due-for-release-in-2016/|title=New Gorillaz Music Due For Release In 2016 \u2013 Music Feeds|date=13 October 2015|website=Musicfeeds.com|accessdate=29 June 2018}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/78wbq9/a-list-of-bands-youre-not-allowed-to-like-anymore-since-alternative-became-a-bad-word|title=A List of Bands You're Not Allowed to Like Anymore Since \"Alternative\" Became a Bad Word|date=27 January 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/gorillaz-contributors-and-discography|title=Inside the Gorillaverse: A Look at Alt-Rock's Best Cartoon Band|website=Metacritic}}</ref> [[hip hop music|hip hop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as hip hop:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/may/13/popandrock.shopping3|title=Gorillaz, Demon Days|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|work=The Guardian|date=13 May 2005|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/album/gorillaz-human/|title=Gorillaz \u2013 'Humanz'|last=Wehner|first=Cyclone|magazine=Music Feeds|date=April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://districtmagazine.ie/the-10-best-gorillaz-collaborations-with-hip-hop-artists/|title=The 10 best Gorillaz collaborations with hip hop artists|last=Davidson|first=Eric|publisher=District|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[Pop music|pop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as pop:\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/07622-gorillaz-the-singles-collection-2001-2011-review|title=Gorillaz |last=Calvert|first=John|magazine=The Quietus|date=23 December 2011|accessdate=22 November 2017}}\n*{{cite book |last = Brown |first = Cass |authorlink = Cass Browne |author2=Gorillaz |title = [[Rise of the Ogre]] |date = 2 November 2006 |publisher = Penguin |location = United States |isbn = 1-59448-931-9 |pages = 43\u20137 }}\n*{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/04/gorillaz-in-10-songs/|title=Gorillaz in 10 Songs|last=Phillips|first=Lior|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[trip hop]],<ref>The following references describe the band as trip hop:\n*{{cite web|last1=Lynch|first1=Joe|title=The Week's Best New Music: Feist, Gorillaz, Mary J. Blige & More|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7776267/best-new-music-feist-gorillaz-mary-j-blige|work=Billboard|accessdate=14 May 2017}}\n*{{cite news |first= Kieran |last= Grant |title= Gorillaz in his midst |date= 20 January 2001 |publisher= Jam! |accessdate= 12 July 2016 |url= http://jam.canoe.com/Music/Artists/B/Blur/2001/01/20/pf-743419.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304191554/http://jam.canoe.com/Music/Artists/B/Blur/2001/01/20/pf-743419.html |archivedate= 4 March 2016 |df= dmy-all }}\n*{{cite news|first=Lisa |last=Lee |title=Miho Hatori Uses Her Noodle |date=1 June 2007 |newspaper=[[AsianWeek]] |url=http://www.asianweek.com/2007/06/01/miho-hatori-uses-her-noodle/ |accessdate=12 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704190236/http://www.asianweek.com/2007/06/01/miho-hatori-uses-her-noodle/ |archivedate=4 July 2015 |df= }}</ref> [[dark pop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as dark pop:\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/top-ten-damon-albarn-albums|title=A 10 Album Introduction To Damon Albarn|date=5 October 2016|website=Theodysseyonline.com|accessdate=29 June 2018}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.vblurpage.com/news/2005/0407.htm|title=Blur News \u2013 Damon talks about \"Demon Days\" and his future projects \u2013 Apr 7, 2005|publisher=}}</ref> [[alternative hip hop]],<ref>The following references cite the band as alternative hip hop or alternative rap:\n*{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/78wbq9/a-list-of-bands-youre-not-allowed-to-like-anymore-since-alternative-became-a-bad-word|title=A List of Bands You're Not Allowed to Like Anymore Since \"Alternative\" Became a Bad Word|date=27 January 2017}}\n*{{cite web|last1=DeGroot|first1=Joey|title=Gorillaz Co-Creator Jamie Hewlett Preps Retrospective Art Book|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/18527/20141203/gorillaz-jamie-hewlett-damon-albarn-preps-retrospective-art-book.htm|work=Music Times|accessdate=4 December 2014|page=1|quote=\"In other Gorillaz news, Damon Albarn recently revealed plans to revive the beloved alternative hip-hop outfit, telling ''The Sydney Morning Herald'' that he intends on releasing a new Gorillaz album in 2016.\"}}</ref> [[rap rock]],<ref>The following references cite the band as rap rock:\n*{{cite web|last=Hermes |first=Will |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-gorillaz-humanz-rings-in-the-apocalypse-in-style-w478893 |title=Review: Gorillaz' 'Humanz' Rings in the Apocalypse in Style |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=27 April 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}\n*{{cite web|author=Sean Palmer |url=http://www.queanbeyanagechronicle.com.au/story/4646118/gorillaz-in-the-midst-of-rap-rock/?cs=5355 |title=Gorillaz in the midst of rap-rock &#124; The Queanbeyan Age |website=Queanbeyanagechronicle.com.au |date=8 May 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> [[indie rock]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diffuser.fm/10-best-gorillaz-songs/|title=10 Best Gorillaz Songs|website=Diffuser.fm|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> [[electronica]],<ref name=\"mfHZ\">{{cite magazine|url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/album/gorillaz-human/|title=Gorillaz \u2013 'Humanz'|last=Wehner|first=Cyclone|magazine=Music Feeds|date=April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[bedroom pop]],<ref>https://www.popmatters.com/gorillaz-the-now-now-2583303134.amp.html</ref> [[dance-rock]],<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-singles-collection-2001-2011-mw0002241721 \"The Singles Collection 2001\u20132011\"]. AllMusic. Retrieved 19 November 2014</ref> [[new wave music|new wave]],<ref name=\"cosHZ\">{{cite magazine|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/04/gorillaz-in-10-songs/|title=Gorillaz in 10 Songs|last=Phillips|first=Lior|magazine=Consequence of Sound|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> [[funk music|funk]]<ref name=\"cosHZ\" /> and [[worldbeat]].<ref name=\"mfHZ\" /> The band's aesthetic and general approach has been described as [[postmodern]].<ref name=\"mfHZ\" /> According to ''[[AllMusic]]'' Gorillaz blend [[Britpop]] and hip-hop,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/gorillaz-mn0000664770|title=Gorillaz \u2013 Biography, Albums, Streaming Links|website=AllMusic|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> while ''[[The Guardian]]'' described the band as \"a sort of [[dub music|dub]]/hip-hop/[[lo-fi music|lo-fi]] indie/[[world music]] hybrid\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/may/13/popandrock.shopping3|title=Gorillaz, Demon Days|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|work=The Guardian|date=13 May 2005|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> According to ''[[PopMatters]]'', the band's early work foreshadowed \"the melding of hip-hop, rock, and [[electronic music|electronic]] elements in pop music\" that grew in significance in the next decade.<ref name=\"pm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/121872-gorillaz-plastic-beach-2496174715.html|title=Gorillaz: Plastic Beach|last=Kabran|first=Michael|website=PopMatters|date=7 March 2010|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Live performances ==\n[[File:Apollo Marquee 2006.jpg|thumb|right|Gorillaz performed ''Demon Days'' at the [[Apollo Theater]] in Harlem, New York in April 2006.]]\nIn March 2001, Gorillaz played their first show at the [[Scala (club)|Scala]] in London before embarking on a tour later that summer, with one date in Paris and two in Japan. The show, called [[Gorillaz Live]], saw the live band playing behind a giant projector screen which covered the whole stage, on which was projected various visuals and images created by Hewlett. After taking a short break over the holidays, the tour resumed with a North American leg in February 2002.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/77222/gorillaz-plan-animated-north-american-tour \"Gorillaz plan animated North American tour\"]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved 30 July 2015</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, Gorillaz performed [[Demon Days Live]], a five night residency at the [[Manchester Opera House]] in Manchester, England in which the album ''[[Demon Days]]'' was presented in its entirety. The event was filmed by an EMI film crew for a DVD release, ''[[Demon Days Live]]'', in late March 2006. It was later announced that an American version of the event would take place in April 2006 at the [[Apollo Theater]] in [[Harlem]], New York. Within an hour of release tickets were sold out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0634.php#060314 |title=NYC Sellout/GES Competition |accessdate=7 January 2007 |date=14 March 2006 |work=fans.gorillaz.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627153053/http://fans.gorillaz.com/news0634.php#060314 |archivedate=27 June 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The show of 6 April was filmed for a live [[webcast]] at [[MSN Video]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/press/2006/apr06/04-04GorillazWebcastPR.mspx |title=MSN Video to Stream Exclusive Live Broadcast of GORILLAZ 'DEMON DAYS LIVE' Concert From the Apollo Theater |accessdate=7 January 2007 |date=5 April 2006 |publisher=[[Microsoft]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090404201739/http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/press/2006/apr06/04-04GorillazWebcastPR.mspx |archivedate=4 April 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> [[Palladia]] (then known as MHD) also broadcast an Apollo Theater show in [[High-definition television|HDTV]] on 31 December 2006.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-156045603.html |title = MTV Networks' MHD: Music High-Definition Rings in the New Year With Exclusive Premiere of 'Gorillaz: Live in Harlem' Concert in High-Def |accessdate =7 January 2007 |date = 19 December 2006 |agency = [[PR Newswire]] }}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n[[File:Gorillaz live 2010.jpg|thumb|Gorillaz performing at the [[Roundhouse (venue)|Roundhouse]] in London, April 2010|upright=1.25|left]]\n\n\nIn March 2010, Gorillaz began a short six date tour as \"rehearsal\" shows for their headlining slot at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]]. The shows were open exclusively to Gorillaz Sub Division fan club members and featured no visuals whatsoever. These performances were the band's first public performances in four years. Gorillaz headlined the final night of the [[Coachella Festival]] on 18 April 2010 as their first proper, full show. On 27 April they were the main guests on ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'' on the BBC. In addition, Gorillaz played a two-night residency at London's Camden Roundhouse (29 and 30 April 2010). [[Mick Jones (The Clash guitarist)|Mick Jones]] and [[Paul Simonon]] of [[the Clash]] performed guitar and bass respectively with the band and more than once in the evening chords from the Clash song \"[[Guns of Brixton]]\" were heard as a subtle reference to their presence.<ref>T\u00e9l\u00e9moustique 5 May 2010, page 59, Roundhouse concert review by Luc Lorf\u00e8vre</ref>\n[[File:Gorillaz at Oslo Spektrum 2.jpg|thumb|right|Gorillaz at the [[Oslo Spektrum]] in November 2017]]\n\nGorillaz embarked on the [[Escape to Plastic Beach Tour]] in October 2010, with some concerts preceding festival dates in the summer, such as at the Byblos Festival in Lebanon, the [[Roskilde Festival]] in Denmark, headlining the [[Glastonbury Festival]] in England and one show at the [[Citadel of Damascus]] in Syria.<ref>{{cite news |title = Gorillaz perform one-off show in Syria |first = Duncan |last = Crawford |publisher = BBC |date = 26 July 2010 |url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/10758917 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Arabian heights: Gorillaz stage historic gig in Syria |first = Stephen |last = Starr |newspaper = The Guardian |date = 27 July 2010 |url = https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/27/gorillaz-historic-gig-syria }}</ref> The tour took them across North America in October, Europe in November, and finally through Australia, New Zealand, and with one date in Hong Kong in December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorillaz will be playing in Beirut and Syria! |author=Gorillaz Official Website |work=gorillaz.com |date=29 June 2010 |url=http://gorillaz.com/news/news/gorillaz-will-be-playing-in-beirut-and-syria |accessdate=30 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701233141/http://gorillaz.com/news/news/gorillaz-will-be-playing-in-beirut-and-syria |archivedate=1 July 2010 |df= }}</ref> During the final show of the tour at the [[Vector Arena]] in [[Auckland]], New Zealand on 21 December 2010, Albarn announced that it would be their final show with the ''[[Plastic Beach]]'' line up.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jason|last=Gregory|url= http://www.gigwise.com/news/60328/Damon-Albarn-Plays-Final-Gig-With-Gorillaz|title=Damon Albarn Plays 'Final Gig' With Gorillaz|work=Gigwise|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 July 2017, Gorillaz embarked upon the [[Humanz Tour]], the band's second world tour and first since 2010. With 53 scheduled shows and lasting over a year, it was Gorillaz' longest tour in their history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7760521/gorillaz-tour-dates-2017|title=Gorillaz Announce 'Humanz' Tour Dates, Join Life Is Beautiful Festival 2017 Lineup|work=Billboard|accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref> On 6 December, Gorillaz announced they would be playing [[Boomtown Fair]] as an \"exclusive one-off UK show\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/gorillaz-perform-exclusive-one-uk-14002389 |title=Gorillaz to perform at Boomtown Fair in one-off UK show |last=Nightingale |first=Laura |date=6 December 2017 |website=getsurrey |access-date=4 April 2018}}</ref> After 53 performances, on 30 March 2018, Humanz Tour concluded in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=980798004444712960|user=gorillaz|title=Final momentz of the #HUMANZWORLDTOUR|author=Gorillaz|date=2 April 2018}}</ref> The tour was followed almost immediately by [[The Now Now Tour]], starting in June 2018 in [[Nuremberg]], [[Germany]]. On 20 October, Gorillaz played \"[[Song 2]]\" by [[Blur (band)|Blur]], at the Demon Dayz Festival, with [[Graham Coxon]], in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/watch-gorillaz-bring-out-blurs-graham-coxon-to-perform-song-2/|title=Watch Gorillaz Bring Out Blur\u2019s Graham Coxon to Perform \"Song 2\"|date=21 October 2018|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=24 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> After 29 performances, on 24 October, The Now Now Tour concluded, in [[Mexico City]].<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1032275042040594439|user=gorillaz|title=#TheNowNow Tour is coming to Mexico|author=Gorillaz|date=22 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/05/gorillaz-north-american-arena-show-festival/|title=Gorillaz announce North American arena tour, Los Angeles Demon Dayz Festival|date=31 May 2018|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=1 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The Now Now Tour had participations of [[The Internet (band)|The Internet]] and [[Little Dragon]].\n\n== Members ==\n{{For|members only in tours|Gorillaz Live|Demon Days Live|Escape to Plastic Beach Tour|Humanz Tour|The Now Now Tour}}\nThis list includes accredited members in the staff lines of each album, does not include: featurings, remixers, mastering, artwork and assistance.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Permanent members'''\n* [[Damon Albarn]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, instrumentation, songwriting, director <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Jamie Hewlett]]&nbsp;\u2013 artwork, [[VJing|visuals]], [[Special effect|FX]], songwriting, video direction <small>(1998\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Current real musicians'''\n* Stephen Sedgwick&nbsp;\u2013 mixing, engineering <small>(2005\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Remi Kabaka Jr.]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming, mixing, engineering <small>(2011\u2013present)</small>\n* Samuel Egglenton&nbsp;\u2013 mixing, engineering <small>(2017\u2013present)</small>\n\n'''Former real musicians'''\n* [[Dan the Automator]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming, songwriting, synthesizers <small>(2001)</small>\n* Tom Girling&nbsp;\u2013 drum programming, mixing, engineering, [[Pro Tools]] <small>(2001)</small>\n* [[Kid Koala]]&nbsp;\u2013 turntables <small>(2001)</small>\n* Toby Whelan&nbsp;\u2013 mixing, engineering <small>(2001)</small>\n* [[Cass Browne]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussion, drum programming <small>(2001\u201305)</small>\n* Jason Cox&nbsp;\u2013 drum programming, additional guitars and bass, mixing, engineering <small>(2001\u201310)</small>\n* Junior Dan&nbsp;\u2013 bass <small>(2001, \"Sorcererz\" (2018))</small>\n* [[Morgan Nicholls]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass <small>(2005)</small>\n* [[Danger Mouse (musician)|Danger Mouse]]&nbsp;\u2013 percussio