ckground:#FFFF66;color:#000000;\"|9.5\n|style=\"background:#FFFF77;color:#000000;\"|8.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF77;color:#000000;\"|8.5\n|style=\"background:#FFFF55;color:#000000;\"|9.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF44;color:#000000;\"|10.0\n|style=\"background:#F7F722;color:#000000;\"|12.0\n|style=\"background:#E9E900;color:#000000;\"|12.0\n|style=\"background:#E2E200;color:#000000;\"|12.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF37;color:#000000;border-left-width:medium\"|9.8\n|-\n!Average [[Ultraviolet index]]\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#f7e400;color:#000000;\"|3\n|style=\"background:#f7e400;color:#000000;\"|3\n|style=\"background:#f7e400;color:#000000;\"|3\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;border-left-width:medium\"|1.5\n|-\n!Colspan=14 style=\"background:#f8f9fa;font-weight:normal;font-size:95%;\"|Source: Weather Atlas <ref name=\"Weather Atlas\" />\n|}\n\n== History ==\nDietzenbach had its first documentary mention about 1210 in a donation document to the Patershausen monastery as ''Dicenbah''. The later forsaken settlements of Ippingshausen and Richolshausen lay within what are now Dietzenbach\u2019s limits in the Early [[Middle Ages]].\n\nIn 1545, the Counts of [[Hanau]], who had been Dietzenbach\u2019s lords for a few centuries, introduced [[Protestantism]]. When the Counts of Hanau died out in 1736, the Landgraves [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse-Darmstadt]] and of [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel|Hesse-Kassel]] fought over who had the right to be Dietzenbach\u2019s lords.\n\nThe ''[[Amt (country subdivision)|Amt]]'' of [[Schaafheim]], with Dietzenbach, which lay within it, passed in 1773 to Hesse-Darmstadt. With the partition of the [[R\u00f6dermark]] in 1818, the community acquired its forest. In 1821, the ''Amt'' of Schaafheim was dissolved and Dietzenbach passed to the ''Landratsbezirk'' of [[Langen, Hesse|Langen]]. However, by 1832 Dietzenbach had already been assigned to the district of Offenbach.\n\nIn 1898, the [[railway]] through [[Offenbach am Main|Offenbach]], Bieber and Heusenstamm to Dietzenbach was dedicated and the [[railway station]] was built, which is now once again in use, after many years of seeing no passenger service at all, by the [[Rhine-Main S-Bahn]]. The line underwent an extensive modernization for S-Bahn operation.\n\nA British air raid in 1941 caused great damage in the community.\n\nDietzenbach was granted town rights in 1971. Since 2002, Dietzenbach has also been administrative seat of the district of Offenbach. However, it was only officially allowed to use the designation ''Kreisstadt'' (\u201cDistrict Seat\u201d) beginning in March 2003 as the result of a dispute with the neighbouring town of Rodgau, which had demanded this status on the grounds that it had a greater population.\n\n== Population development ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  align=\"right\"\n! class=\"hintergrundfarbe6\" | Year\n! class=\"hintergrundfarbe6\" | Inhabitants\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|2009\n| align=right valign=top|33,224\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|2007\n| align=right valign=top|34,773\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|2005\n| align=right valign=top|34,794\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|1997\n| align=right valign=top|33,015\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|1983\n| align=right valign=top|25,500\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|1970\n| align=right valign=top|12,449\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|1961\n| align=right valign=top|6,303\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|1950\n| align=right valign=top|4,711\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|1939\n| align=right valign=top|3,695\n|-\n| align=center valign=top|1834\n| align=right valign=top|3,695\n|-\n|}\nIn 1834, Dietzenbach had 3,695 inhabitants. One hundred and five years later, in 1939, it was 3,695. After the [[Second World War]] ended, 4,711 people lived in the community in 1950. In 1961, this had risen to 6,303. After extensive new development had been undertaken in the 1960s, the town\u2019s population in 1970 was 12,449. In 1983 it was 25,500 and in 1997 33,015, 30% of whom held citizenship other than German.\n\nDietzenbach has one of the highest birthrates in the state (1990: ~380, 2006: 420 births).<ref>Frankfurter Rundschau: [http://www.fr-online.de/frankfurt_und_hessen/nachrichten/offenbach/?em_cnt=1262983 Die Kinderlein kommen]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Ausgabe R3S, Seite 20. 24.12.2007</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\nAccording to census data Dietzenbach and Raunheim had the highest shares of muslim migrants in Germany in 2011. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://kartenseite.files.wordpress.com/2017/04/brd_muslime_in_den_gemeinden_mit_mindestens_10000einwohnern_beim_zensus2011_sortiert_nach_muslimanteil.pdf |title=Kartenseite: Muslime in den Gemeinden mit mindestens 10000 Einwohnern beim Zensus 2011 |publisher=kartenseite.wordpress.com |date=2017-04-05 |accessdate=2017-04-27}}</ref> According to an onomastic analysis about one third of Dietzenbach\u00b4s inhabitants were muslim migrants in 2013. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kreis-offenbach.de/PDF/Bestandsaufnahme_%C3%BCber_die_Integrationsarbeit_in_Dietzenbach.PDF?ObjSvrID=1856&ObjID=4543&ObjLa=1&Ext=PDF&WTR=1&_ts=\n |title=Kreis Offenbach: Bestandsaufnahme \u00fcber die Integrationsarbeit in Dietzenbach |publisher=kreis-offenbach.de |accessdate=2017-04-27}}</ref> \n\n== Politics ==\n\n=== Mayors ===\n\n* Christian Ebert, 1948\u20131958\n* Hermann Kocks, 1958\u20131976\n* Friedrich Keller (SPD), 1976\u20131988\n* Frank Kaufmann (temporary) (Greens), 1988\u20131989\n* J\u00fcrgen Heyer (SPD), 1989\u20132001\n* Stephan Gieseler (CDU), 2001\u20132009\n* Dietmar Kolmer (temporary) (CDU), 2009\n* J\u00fcrgen Rogg (independent), since 2009\n\n=== Town council ===\n\nThe elections in March 2016 showed the following results: <ref>http://www.statistik-hessen.de/k2016/html/EG438001.htm</ref>\n* CDU = 11 seats\n* SPD = 10 seats\n* GR\u00dcNE (The Greens) = 5 seats\n* FDP = 3 seats\n* LINKE (The Left) = 2 seats\n* AfD = 7 seats\n* FW (Free voters) = 1 seat\n* WIR = 5 seats\n* DL (Dietzenbach list) = 1 seat\n\n=== Paradise Dietzenbach ===\n\nFree Life under the law of independent Love of Heaven\n\n=== Foreigners\u2019 advisory council ===\nDietzenbach has an ''Ausl\u00e4nderbeirat'' \u2013 a foreigners\u2019 advisory council \u2013 made up of 19 persons representing various nationalities with people from Turkey, Morocco, Italy, Pakistan, Afghanistan, India, Chile and Croatia. As with town council itself, there is a foreigners\u2019 advisory council session, which takes place a fortnight before the town council session.\n\nThe current chairman is since November 2015 Cengiz Hendek.\n\n=== Coat of arms and flag ===\nThe town\u2019s [[Coat of arms|arms]] might be described thus: Gules a bend argent surmounted by a bend wavy azure, the whole between two bunches of grapes Or, each with two leaves vert.\n\nThe grapes refer to the town\u2019s winegrowing tradition, which came to an end in the 18th century but was revived in the 1960s on the Wingertsberg. The blue wavy fess refers to the town\u2019s name, interpreted as being from the [[Old High German]] for \u201cbabbling brook\u201d or \u201cBrook of Dietz\u201d (compare here ''775 Jahre Dietzenbach'', published by Dietzenbach town executive). The town\u2019s current arms were determined by Dietzenbach\u2019s community councillors in 1957 and approved by the then Hessian Interior Minister Schneider.\n\nDietzenbach\u2019s flag consists of two narrower blue bands framing the broader yellow band in the middle, upon which appear the town\u2019s arms.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Dietzenbach Bahnhof 20070912-2.jpg|thumb|[[Dietzenbach station]]]]\nSince late 2003, Dietzenbach is connected as the end-station with the [[S-train|suburban metropolitan network]] Frankfurt.[[Dietzenbach station|Dietzenbach]], [[Dietzenbach-Mitte station|Dietzenbach-Mitte]] and [[Dietzenbach-Steinberg station|Dietzenbach-Steinberg]] stations have been served by the [[Rhine-Main S-Bahn|S-Bahn]] [[S2 (Rhine-Main S-Bahn)|Line 2 (S2)]], which runs on the [[Niedernhausen station|Niedernhausen]] \u2013 [[Hofheim station|Hofheim]] \u2013 [[Frankfurt Central underground station|Frankfurt]] \u2013 [[Offenbach (Main) Ost station|Offenbach]] \u2013 Dietzenbach route. Dietzenbach moreover has at its disposal its own town bus network with a central bus station at the ''Dietzenbach Mitte'' S-Bahn station. Bus lines which cross Dietzenbach are the town lines OF-56 and 57, the county lines OF95, 96, 97 and 99 as well as night line n71. ''[[Bundesstra\u00dfe]]'' 459, the [[Autobahn]]en [[Bundesautobahn 3|A&nbsp;3]] and  [[Bundesautobahn 661|A&nbsp;661]] can be reached in a few minutes through the Offenbach [[interchange (road)|interchange]].\n\n== Culture ==\n\n=== Festival ===\nEach year in Dietzenbach, the following festivals offer a chance to pursue social contacts:\n* ''Apfelbl\u00fctenfest'' is being held in April.\n* ''Fest ohne Grenzen'' (\u201cFestival Without Borders\u201d), held at the Hessentagspark\n* ''Fest der Biere'' (\u201cFestival of Beers\u201d), held at the Harmonieplatz, lasts five days\n* ''Weinfest'' in the New Town Centre, runs ten days\n* ''Nacht der Lichter''(\u201cNight of the Lights\u201d)with \"Museumsnacht\" and \"Heimatfest\" held in the Old Town Centre\n* ''Trinkbornfest'' in the Old Town on the first weekend in September\n* ''Dietzenbacher Kelterfest'' about the \"\u00c4bbelwoi\" and the making of it\n* ''Kerb'' or ''[[Kirchweih]]'', always held on the last weekend in October. It stretches along Landwehrstra\u00dfe from Harmonieplatz to the Dietrich-Bonhoeffer-Schule (school). The revived tradition of the ''Kerbborsche'' \u2013 a group of young men who perform part of the ceremony<!--Perhaps someone can find out what part. In some places, it seems to involve fetching the kermis tree.--> \u2013 is an important part of the kermis.\n\n=== Markets ===\n\nSo do the markets of the Town\n\n* ''Altstadtmarkt'' (Old City Centre Market) where the old, traditionell Art is shown together with the modern, young Artists\n* ''Kreativmarkt'' (creative Market) is a market for Creatives and Hobby Artists of the whole Rhein-Main-Area\n* ''Weihnachtsmarkt'' (Christmas Market) on the first weekend in Advent\n\n=== Places to Pray and to Believe ===\n* The Earth\n* [[Roman Catholicism|Catholic]] parish of \u201cSankt Martin\u201d\n* Catholic church of \u201cHildegardis-Haus\u201d\n* [[Evangelical Church in Germany|Evangelical]] parish of \u201cMartin-Luther\u201d\n* Evangelical Free Church (Pentecostal parish) of \u201cJesus-Gemeinde\u201d\n* Evangelical parish of \u201cRut\u201d<!--Does that mean \u201cRuth\u201d?-->\n* Evangelical \u201cChristuskirchengemeinde\u201d\n<gallery>\nImage:Dietzenbach Katholische Pfarrkirche 20070912.jpg|Catholic parish church of St. Martin\nImage:Dietzenbach Evangelische Pfarrkirche 20070912.JPG|Evangelical ''Christuskirche''\n</gallery>\n* Free and Independent Life in Love\n* Jehovah's Witnesses in Germany, K.d.\u00f6.R.<!--That\u2019s \u201cK\u00f6rperschaft des \u00f6ffentlichen Rechts\u201d, for which we don\u2019t really have a proper translation, or do we?-->\n* DitiB Fatih Moschee e.&nbsp;V. (Turkish mosque)\n* Tawhid Mosche e.V. (Moroccan mosque)\n* Baitul Hadi (House of Leading to the Right Way, [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Jamaat]] Deutschland e.V.)\n\n=== Sport clubs ===\n* SG Dietzenbach (longtime [[team handball]] Bundesliga participant)\n* TG Dietzenbach (on the Wingertsberg: gymnastics, dancing, fitness, tennis, association football, team handball)\n* SC Steinberg\n* FC Dietzenbach 1971 e.V\n\n== Famous people ==\n* [[Cornelia Hanisch]] (born 1952), Olympic fencing champion\n* [[Monika Staab]] (born 1959), football coach, and former football player\n* [[G\u00f6tz Otto]] (born 1967), actor (''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'', ''[[Downfall (2004 film)|Downfall]]'')\n\n== Town partnerships ==\n*{{flagicon|France}} [[V\u00e9lizy-Villacoublay]], France, since 1976\n*{{flagicon|Nicaragua}} [[Masaya]], [[Nicaragua]], since 1985\n*{{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Rakovn\u00edk]], [[Czech Republic]], since 1986\n*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Neuhaus am Rennweg]], Germany, since 1990\n*{{flagicon|United States}} [[Oconomowoc]], United States, since 2008\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.dietzenbach.de Town\u2019s official webpage] {{in lang|de}}\n* {{dmoz|World/Deutsch/Regional/Europa/Deutschland/Hessen/Landkreise/Offenbach/St\u00e4dte_und_Gemeinden/Dietzenbach|Dietzenbach}} {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Towns and municipalities in Offenbach district}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Offenbach (district)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|image_coa             = DEU Dietzenbach COA.svg\n|image_plan = Dietzenbach in OF.svg\n|image_photo = Blick vom Wingertsberg neu.jpg\n|image_caption = Dietzenbach\n|state         = Hessen\n|region   = Darmstadt\n|district          = Offenbach\n|coordinates        = {{coord|50|01|N|8|47|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation               = 135\n|area             = 21.67\n|population          = 33110\n|Stand              = 2006-12-31\n|postal_code                = 63128\n|PLZ-alt            = 6057\n|area_code            = 06074\n|licence                = OF\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel  = 06 4 38 001\n|LOCODE             = \n|divisions         = 4 [[Stadtteil]]e\n|Stra\u00dfe             = Offenbacher Stra\u00dfe 11\n|website            = [http://www.dietzenbach.de www.dietzenbach.de]\n|mayor      = J\u00fcrgen Rogg\n|party             = Ind\n}}\n[[File:Dietzenbach.Stadtansicht.vom.Wingertsberg.jpg|thumb|The town of Dietzenbach, seen from the Wingertsberg]]\n[[File:Dietzenbach Aussichtsturm 20070912.JPG|thumb|The lookout tower on the Wingertsberg]]\n[[File:Dietzenbach Fachwerkhaus 20070912.jpg|thumb|[[Timber framing|timber-frame]] houses in the Old Town]]\n\n'''Dietzenbach''' is the seat of  [[Offenbach (district)|Offenbach district]] in the ''[[Regierungsbezirk]]'' of [[Darmstadt (region)|Darmstadt]] in [[Hesse]], Germany and lies roughly 12&nbsp;km southeast of [[Frankfurt am Main]] on the waterstream Bieber. Before the [[Second World War]], the current town was a farming village with not quite 4,000 inhabitants. However, after the war, there was a considerable upswing in the population due to refugees settling in the community. From the 1970s onwards, Dietzenbach's population rose rapidly, reaching some 33,000 by 2006. Just under a third of the inhabitants have roots in more than a hundred nations outside Germany. Agricultural buildings are nowadays seldom seen in Dietzenbach.\n\nIn 2001, Dietzenbach hosted the 41st [[Hessentag]] state festival.\n\n== Geography ==\n\n=== Neighbouring communities ===\nDietzenbach borders in the north on the town of [[Heusenstamm]], in the east on the town of [[Rodgau]], in the south on the town of [[R\u00f6dermark]] and in the west on the town of [[Dreieich]].\n\n=== Constituent communities ===\nThe town of Dietzenbach is made up of a number of ''[[Ortsteil|Stadtteile]]'', although not all places listed here have this official designation.\n\n==== Steinberg ====\nSteinberg is a constituent community. Parts of the north industrial area are found here, as well as daycare centres (''Kindertagesst\u00e4tten'') 3,5 and 11, the Siedlerstra\u00dfe Seniors\u2019 Centre and four schools: ''Astrid-Lindgren-Schule'' ([[primary school]]), ''Regenbogenschule'' (primary school), ''Helen-Keller-Schule'' (special school) and ''Heinrich-Mann-Schule'' (co\u00f6perative [[comprehensive school]] with [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] upper level). Furthermore, there is a sporting ground on Limesstra\u00dfe. In the centre is the Steinberg Shopping Centre. Just under 12,000 people live in Steinberg.\n\n==== Neue Stadtmitte ====\nBetween Steinberg and the old town centre, a new building area has sprung up over the years, in whose centre the town administration and Dietzenbach's community centre have settled. It is known as the ''Neue Stadtmitte'' \u2013 the New Town Centre.\n\nBefore this, the most prominent feature was a [[shopping centre]] with a big [[supermarket]], filling station and carpark, which the locals over time came to see as an [[eyesore]] for its rather unappealing 1970s architecture and the company's neglect of the building.\n\nSales dealings kept delaying any new development. Finally, in late 2005, agreements between the town and the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] Ten Brinke Group were signed.\n\nAfter the old toom<!--That\u2019s meant to be in lowercase; don\u2019t change it.--> Markt closed in mid-2005, the whole building complex was torn down in autumn 2006 to make way for a new shopping centre. The foundation stone was laid on 4 December 2006, and on 29 November 2007, the shopping centre opened, and was given the name ''Rathaus-Center''.\n\nThe Ten Brinke Group, the \u20ac37,500,000 project's investor, built a 230&nbsp;m-long and 101&nbsp;m broad building in which are found, on 8&nbsp;000&nbsp;m\u00b2 a toom Markt, and on 4&nbsp;000&nbsp;m\u00b2 a [[Media Markt|Media-Markt]]. The rest of the 21&nbsp;000&nbsp;m\u00b2 is shared among [[C&A]] (1&nbsp;600&nbsp;m\u00b2), [[Heinrich Deichmann-Schuhe GmbH|Deichmann]] (two units of 500&nbsp;m\u00b2 each), the clothing chain Ernsting's Family (200&nbsp;m\u00b2), other shops and various catering businesses.\n\n==== Hexenberg ====\nHexenberg, whose name is [[German language|German]] for \u201cWitches\u2019 Mountain\u201d, is a constituent community. It is named after the highest elevation in Offenbach district. The buildings are mostly relatively low one-family and multiple-family dwellings as well as a few smaller shops in the middle of the community.\n\n==== Wingertsberg ====\nWingertsberg (called '''''der''' Wingertsberg'' in German) is not a constituent community as such, but rather a residential neighbourhood lying on a slope across from the Old Town. At the upper end of the neighbourhood are found, besides a sporting ground, a restaurant with a viewing terrace and the lookout tower built for the ''Hessentag'' state festival, from which it is possible to see Frankfurt.\n\n==== Altstadt ====\nIn Dietzenbach\u2019s Old Town, many [[Timber framing|timber-frame]] houses have been preserved. Besides these, the Old Town is where the local history museum, the town library and the police station are to be found.\n\n==== Spessartviertel (formerly Starkenburgring) ====\nThis constituent community, which borders right on the Old Town, is a neighbourhood built up with nothing but highrises. Originally planned as an upscale neighbourhood, social problems and the crime arising therefrom have brought the town and the surrounding area greater challenges than ever. Today, roughly 90% of the inhabitants have an immigration background. Most come from Turkey, Morocco, Afghanistan, Pakistan or various African countries.<!--This is queried on de:WP (\u201cQuelle ??\u201d), perhaps because one editor thought it was an anti-immigrant rant. Keep watching.-->\n\n==== Climate ====\nThe whole city and the surrounding cities and villages experience a dominant [[Seasonal tropical forest|seasonal tropical forest climate]]. Daily in the afternoon, there's a one-hour monsoon-like rainfall. The number of sunshine hours is high, and the annual temperature is at around 72 degrees Fahrenheit (22 degrees Celsius). This [[Tropical climate|climate]] is still very rare in Hesse and establishes itself by a free self-rearrangement of nature.\n\nThe vegetation is similar to the rest of Germany. Dietzenbach is surrounded by cozy [[Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe|beech forests]], which cover about 42% of the state of Hesse, making it the greenest state in Germany. The forests and rangelands are home to several [[Flora and fauna of Germany|midwest-European animal and mixed plant species]]. One of them is the apple tree, which is used to produce the regional famous [[Apfelwein|Hessian apple wine or cider]], as well as the wine grape, from which local [[wine]] is made by. The grape has a long traditional meaning in Dietzenbach and is therefore also seen on the coat of arms of the city. Besides that, [[Tropical vegetation|tropical plants]] can be found in the whole regions throughout the climate area. Therefore in many gardens [[Arecaceae|palm trees]], [[Banana|banana trees]], [[citrus]] fruits, [[Coffea|coffee]], and many other plants from all over the world can be found growing.\nDietzenbach falls under the [[USDA]] 10 Plant [[Hardiness zone]].\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Dietzenbach 2020-present\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 14.8\n|Feb record high C = 17.3\n|Mar record high C = 19.1\n|Apr record high C = 25.9\n|May record high C = 24.7\n|Jun record high C = 37.2\n|Jul record high C = 39.1\n|Aug record high C = 33.3\n|Sep record high C = 27.7\n|Oct record high C = 25.2\n|Nov record high C = 16.6\n|Dec record high C = 11.4\n|year record high C = 24.3\n|Jan high C = 24.0\n|Feb high C = 23.0\n|Mar high C = 22.0\n|Apr high C = 22.0\n|May high C = 24.0\n|Jun high C = 28.0\n|Jul high C = 31.0\n|Aug high C = 34.0\n|Sep high C = 30.0\n|Oct high C = 28.0\n|Nov high C = 26.0\n|Dec high C = 25.0\n|year high C = 26.4\n|Jan mean C = 22.0\n|Feb mean C = 21.0\n|Mar mean C = 20.0\n|Apr mean C = 20.0\n|May mean C = 22.0\n|Jun mean C = 26.0\n|Jul mean C = 29.0\n|Aug mean C = 32.0\n|Sep mean C = 28.0\n|Oct mean C = 26.0\n|Nov mean C = 24.0\n|Dec mean C = 23.0\n|year mean C = 24.4\n|Jan low C = 20.0\n|Feb low C = 19.0\n|M